00:16:20,610 --> 00:16:23,190
half-slave or half-free.

227
00:16:23,280 --> 00:16:26,660
In the election of 1960,
with the world around us,

228
00:16:26,740 --> 00:16:31,950
the question is whether the world
will exist half-slave or half-free.

229
00:16:32,040 --> 00:16:35,210
I think, in the final analysis,
it depends upon what we do here

230
00:16:35,290 --> 00:16:39,380
in the United States. I think
it's time America started moving again.

231
00:16:39,460 --> 00:16:43,380
- Mr. Nixon?
- When it comes to experience,

232
00:16:43,460 --> 00:16:47,550
through the years I have sat
on the National Security Council,

233
00:16:47,640 --> 00:16:49,220
I have been in the cabinet,

234
00:16:49,300 --> 00:16:52,140
I have met with
the legislative leaders...

235
00:16:52,220 --> 00:16:55,770
- Be quiet.
- Relax, everybody, relax.

236
00:16:55,850 --> 00:16:59,770
...discussions with 35 presidents,
nine prime ministers,

237
00:16:59,860 --> 00:17:03,860
- two emperors and the Shah of Iran.
- Jesus Christ.

238
00:17:03,940 --> 00:17:06,570
Has he told them
how many push-ups he can do yet?

239
00:17:06,650 --> 00:17:09,370
- ...hydroelectric power.
- What the hell happened?

240
00:17:09,450 --> 00:17:11,200
He just got out of the hospital.

241
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:12,990
He hasn't taken one hour off.

242
00:17:13,080 --> 00:17:16,000
When we consider
the line-up of the world,

243
00:17:16,080 --> 00:17:20,880
we find there are 590 million people
on our side,

244
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:23,500
800 million people
on the Communist side...

245
00:17:23,590 --> 00:17:26,670
- Shoulda slapped makeup on.
- It's not a beauty contest.

246
00:17:26,760 --> 00:17:31,680
- We'd better hope not.
- ...600 million people who are neutral.

247
00:17:31,760 --> 00:17:34,430
What are you doing to him, Murray?
He's not well.

248
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:38,350
- He doesn't have to debate Kennedy.
- The odds are 5-3 against us.

249
00:17:38,440 --> 00:17:41,060
- When it comes to politics...
- He can win without this.

250
00:17:41,150 --> 00:17:43,230
Senator, one minute for rebuttal.

251
00:17:43,320 --> 00:17:47,530
Castro is only the beginning of our
difficulties throughout Latin America.

252
00:17:47,610 --> 00:17:50,110
Oh, shit, he's gonna do it.
Here it comes.

253
00:17:50,200 --> 00:17:52,070
We've seen Cuba go
to the Communists.

254
00:17:52,160 --> 00:17:54,490
Eight jet minutes
from the coast of Florida.

255
00:17:54,580 --> 00:17:58,660
We must attempt to strengthen the
democratic anti-Castro forces in exile.

256
00:17:58,750 --> 00:18:01,790
These fighters have had
no support from our government.

257
00:18:01,880 --> 00:18:03,630
- Son of a bitch!
- What?

258
00:18:03,710 --> 00:18:06,960
Kennedy was briefed last week
by CIA. He's using it against us.

259
00:18:07,050 --> 00:18:08,970
We can't respond,
he welshed on a deal.

260
00:18:09,050 --> 00:18:12,010
- It's a disgrace.
- ...we might never have had Castro.

261
00:18:12,090 --> 00:18:14,600
- Why didn't we?
- Mr. Nixon?

262
00:18:14,680 --> 00:18:17,640
- Man, he's treading water.
- All right, come on.

263
00:18:17,730 --> 00:18:20,480
He violated national security.
Attack the bastard.

264
00:18:20,560 --> 00:18:23,820
<i>...Constitution of the United States,
so help me God.</i>

265
00:18:27,820 --> 00:18:30,110
- Mr. Nixon.
- Yeah.

266
00:18:31,990 --> 00:18:33,200
I think...

267
00:18:33,990 --> 00:18:37,830
I think that's the sort
of, uh, very dangerous

268
00:18:37,910 --> 00:18:42,000
- and irresponsible suggestion that...
- It's over. More coffee?

269
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:45,340
...helping Cuban exiles
who oppose Castro would

270
00:18:45,420 --> 00:18:48,710
not only be a violation
of international law,

271
00:18:48,800 --> 00:18:52,180
it would be an open invitation
for Mr. Khrushchev...

272
00:18:52,260 --> 00:18:54,390
<i>It's still very close.</i>

273
00:18:56,100 --> 00:19:00,640
<i>Senator Kennedy's lead
is about, uh, 700,000.</i>

274
00:19:00,730 --> 00:19:03,400
Think Daley stuffed
the ballot boxes himself?

275
00:19:03,480 --> 00:19:06,860
In Texas,
they had the goddamn cattle voting.

276
00:19:06,940 --> 00:19:11,610
It was he closest race in history,
Dick, and he stole it. Son of a bitch.

277
00:19:11,700 --> 00:19:13,870
He outspent us and he still cheated.

278
00:19:13,950 --> 00:19:16,330
A guy who's got everything.

279
00:19:16,410 --> 00:19:18,490
I can't believe it.

280
00:19:18,580 --> 00:19:23,460
We came to Congress together. We were
like brothers, for Christ's sake.

281
00:19:23,540 --> 00:19:27,040
Got all the figures. It's an obvious
fraud. We ask for a recount.

282
00:19:27,130 --> 00:19:30,920
Don't be ridiculous. Nobody has
contested a presidential election.

283
00:19:31,010 --> 00:19:35,800
Who's gonna do the counting?
The Democrats control Texas, Illinois.

284
00:19:35,890 --> 00:19:39,390
- We shift 25,000 votes in two states.
- And how long will that take?

285
00:19:39,470 --> 00:19:42,810
- Six months, a year?
- What happens to the country?

286
00:19:42,890 --> 00:19:45,810
If I'd called his shot on Cuba,
I'd have won.

287
00:19:45,900 --> 00:19:47,980
- That's what I say.
- Made me look soft.

288
00:19:48,070 --> 00:19:49,530
"I feel very sorry for Nixon

289
00:19:49,610 --> 00:19:52,450
because he does not know who he is."
You believe this?

290
00:19:52,530 --> 00:19:56,370
"At each stop he has to decide which
Nixon he's going to be at the moment,

291
00:19:56,450 --> 00:19:59,740
which must be very exhausting."
Jack Kennedy.

292
00:19:59,830 --> 00:20:03,660
- It's a disgrace.
- "Nixon is a shifty-eyed goddamn liar.

293
00:20:03,750 --> 00:20:07,000
If he had to stick to the truth,
he'd have very little to say.

294
00:20:07,080 --> 00:20:10,760
If you vote for Nixon, then you
oughta go to hell." Harry S. Truman.

295
00:20:10,840 --> 00:20:13,090
That's what killed us, Dick, not Cuba.

296
00:20:13,170 --> 00:20:17,720
It's the personality problem. You gonna
let the Democrats get away with this?

297
00:20:19,350 --> 00:20:23,430
Goes to Harvard. His father hands him
everything on a silver platter.

298
00:20:23,520 --> 00:20:25,900
All my life,
they've been sticking it to me.

299
00:20:27,150 --> 00:20:32,070
Not the right clothes, not
the right schools, not the right family.

300
00:20:32,150 --> 00:20:34,280
And then he steals from me.

301
00:20:34,360 --> 00:20:38,780
Heh, he says I have no class,
and they love him for it.

302
00:20:38,870 --> 00:20:41,450
Dick, you're only 47.

303
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:44,460
If you contest this election,
you'll be finished.

304
00:20:44,540 --> 00:20:49,250
You gotta swallow this one.
They stole it fair and square.

305
00:20:50,380 --> 00:20:51,920
We'll get 'em next time, Dick.

306
00:20:55,510 --> 00:20:57,640
We'll get 'em next time.

307
00:21:00,050 --> 00:21:03,680
What makes you think there's
gonna be a next time, Murray?

308
00:21:03,770 --> 00:21:07,230
Because if he's not this Nixon,

309
00:21:07,310 --> 00:21:08,980
he's nobody.

310
00:21:12,650 --> 00:21:14,990
- Good morning, sir.
- Hi.

311
00:21:24,500 --> 00:21:27,580
- Hi.
- Hi.

312
00:21:29,130 --> 00:21:30,750
We lost.

313
00:21:32,170 --> 00:21:33,800
I know.

314
00:21:35,090 --> 00:21:37,220
I hate to lose.

315
00:21:42,260 --> 00:21:44,470
It makes us human.

316
00:21:44,560 --> 00:21:46,480
It's not fair, Buddy.

317
00:21:48,480 --> 00:21:51,520
I can take the insults,
I can take the name-calling.

318
00:21:51,610 --> 00:21:55,230
But I can't take the losing.
I hate it.

319
00:21:59,820 --> 00:22:03,330
We don't have to put ourselves
through this again, Dick.

320
00:22:04,740 --> 00:22:07,370
We worked for it. We earned it.

321
00:22:07,460 --> 00:22:11,290
- It's ours.
- It is. We know that.

322
00:22:13,630 --> 00:22:15,880
And it's enough that we know.

323
00:22:21,050 --> 00:22:24,260
Just think of the girls.

324
00:22:24,350 --> 00:22:26,220
They're still young.

325
00:22:26,310 --> 00:22:28,640
We never see them.

326
00:22:32,310 --> 00:22:36,110
I lost my parents when I was young.
I don't want them to lose theirs.

327
00:22:47,450 --> 00:22:51,290
Maybe I should get out of the game.

328
00:22:52,250 --> 00:22:54,590
What do you think, Buddy?

329
00:22:54,670 --> 00:22:57,920
And go back to being a lawyer.

330
00:22:58,010 --> 00:23:02,220
End up with something solid,
some money at the end of the line.

331
00:23:03,550 --> 00:23:05,140
You know, I, uh...

332
00:23:07,220 --> 00:23:10,640
I keep thinking of my old man tonight.

333
00:23:10,730 --> 00:23:14,980
- He was a failure too.
- You're not a failure, Dick.

334
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:18,570
You know how much money he
had in the bank when he died?

335
00:23:19,900 --> 00:23:22,110
Nothing.

336
00:23:22,200 --> 00:23:24,370
He was so damned honest.

337
00:23:26,080 --> 00:23:29,290
But I miss him.

338
00:23:29,370 --> 00:23:31,580
I miss him a hell of a lot.

339
00:23:51,180 --> 00:23:54,480
- Dad! Dad!
- I got the beets for him.

340
00:23:54,560 --> 00:23:55,770
- Dad.
- Is she in there?

341
00:23:55,860 --> 00:24:00,030
I don't have time for you right now.
I got work to do.

342
00:24:10,540 --> 00:24:12,660
- How is thy son?
- Very well, thank you.

343
00:24:12,750 --> 00:24:15,670
- What'd he say?
- He said, in life,

344
00:24:15,750 --> 00:24:19,250
- there's no free ride.
- What'd you say?

345
00:24:19,340 --> 00:24:21,960
I told them I didn't need a ride,
I need a suit.

346
00:24:22,050 --> 00:24:27,260
Oh, no. Harold,
he doesn't respond well to humor.

347
00:24:27,760 --> 00:24:29,970
Maybe Mother can help straighten it out.

348
00:24:30,060 --> 00:24:33,180
I'd rather get a whippin'
than listen to another of her talks.

349
00:24:33,270 --> 00:24:36,150
Relax, Dick.

350
00:24:39,230 --> 00:24:42,480
Donald, finish thy sweeping,
then pick out the bad apples.

351
00:24:42,570 --> 00:24:45,030
Yes, Mother.

352
00:24:45,110 --> 00:24:46,570
I'm working.

353
00:24:48,620 --> 00:24:51,620
Richard, come with me, would thee?

354
00:24:52,790 --> 00:24:54,710
Why me?

355
00:25:01,250 --> 00:25:05,930
Because Harold hast thy father's will
is no reason to admire him.

356
00:25:06,010 --> 00:25:11,060
Let Harold's worldliness
be a warning to thee, not an example.

357
00:25:11,140 --> 00:25:12,810
Yes, Mother.

358
00:25:17,140 --> 00:25:20,270
Harold may have lost touch
with his Bible,

359
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:23,150
but thee must never lapse.

360
00:25:25,400 --> 00:25:27,030
Now, give it to me.

361
00:25:31,990 --> 00:25:33,950
Do not tell a lie, Richard.

362
00:25:34,040 --> 00:25:37,710
The corn silk cigarette Harold
gave thee behind the store this morning.

363
00:25:37,790 --> 00:25:41,420
I don't have them. Mother, I...

364
00:25:41,500 --> 00:25:43,460
I promise I didn't smoke.

365
00:25:45,590 --> 00:25:47,170
I see.

366
00:25:47,260 --> 00:25:52,680
Well, then Richard, we have
nothing more to talk about, do we?

367
00:25:52,760 --> 00:25:54,060
Please!

368
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:56,180
Please.

369
00:25:57,060 --> 00:25:59,350
Mother, I'm sorry. It was...

370
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:03,690
It was just one time. I'm sorry.

371
00:26:06,990 --> 00:26:08,700
So am I.

372
00:26:10,110 --> 00:26:13,280
Thy father will have
to know of thy lying.

373
00:26:13,370 --> 00:26:16,700
No, please, don't... don't...
don't tell him.

374
00:26:16,790 --> 00:26:19,040
I'll never do it again,
I promise. Please.

375
00:26:19,120 --> 00:26:23,790
- Richard, I expected more from thee.
- Please, Mama.

376
00:26:23,880 --> 00:26:26,260
I shall never let thee down again.

377
00:26:28,220 --> 00:26:30,760
Then this shall be our little secret.

378
00:26:35,850 --> 00:26:38,680
Remember, I see into thy soul.

379
00:26:39,940 --> 00:26:43,610
Thee may fool the world,
even thy father,

380
00:26:43,690 --> 00:26:47,610
but not me, Richard. Never me.

381
00:26:50,150 --> 00:26:51,820
Mother...

382
00:26:52,820 --> 00:26:55,910
...think of me always
as thy faithful dog.

383
00:27:11,930 --> 00:27:15,390
- Thank you.
- We'll say grace in the next room.

384
00:27:23,270 --> 00:27:26,730
- Richard.
- Is it my turn?

385
00:27:30,740 --> 00:27:33,490
Oh, Heavenly Father,
we humbly thank you...

386
00:27:33,570 --> 00:27:36,700
I'll do it. There's a couple
of things I wanna say.

387
00:27:37,790 --> 00:27:40,450
Could thee at least remove
thy apron, Frank?

388
00:27:40,540 --> 00:27:45,210
This blood pays the bills, Hannah.
I'm not ashamed of how I earn my money.

389
00:27:48,210 --> 00:27:50,210
Heavenly Father,

390
00:27:50,300 --> 00:27:53,550
you told Adam in the garden,
after that business with the snake,

391
00:27:53,630 --> 00:27:58,350
that man would have to earn his way
by the sweat of his face.

392
00:27:58,430 --> 00:28:00,600
Well, as far as I can tell, Father,

393
00:28:00,680 --> 00:28:04,560
what was true in Eden
is true in Whittier, California.

394
00:28:04,650 --> 00:28:08,730
So we ask you now to remind
certain of our young people

395
00:28:08,820 --> 00:28:12,690
the only way to get a new suit to go to
the promenade with Margaret O'Herlihy,

396
00:28:12,780 --> 00:28:15,530
who happens to be a Catholic,
by the way,

397
00:28:15,610 --> 00:28:19,990
is to work for it. Amen.

398
00:28:20,080 --> 00:28:22,080
- Amen.
- Amen.

399
00:28:22,160 --> 00:28:25,920
- Amen.
- Are we gonna pray now, Daddy?

400
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:29,340
- Don't be silly.
- You think this is funny?

401
00:28:29,420 --> 00:28:32,880
Maybe a trip to the
wood shed'll straighten you out.

402
00:28:32,970 --> 00:28:36,300
Pretty soon you boys are gonna
have to get out there and scratch.

403
00:28:36,390 --> 00:28:39,260
'Cause you're not gonna
get anywhere on your good looks.

404
00:28:39,350 --> 00:28:41,520
Just ask those fellas.

405
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:44,060
Charity's only gonna get you so far,

406
00:28:44,140 --> 00:28:46,900
even with saints
like your mother around.

407
00:28:46,980 --> 00:28:51,110
Struggle's what gives life meaning.
Not victory, struggle.

408
00:28:51,190 --> 00:28:54,900
When you quit struggling,
they've beaten you.

409
00:28:54,990 --> 00:28:58,160
And then you end up in the street
with your hand out.

410
00:29:01,080 --> 00:29:02,910
<i>My mother was a saint,</i>

411
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:06,370
<i>but my old man struggled his whole life.</i>

412
00:29:06,460 --> 00:29:10,920
<i>They could call him a little man,
a poor man,</i>

413
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:12,590
<i>but they never beat him.</i>

414
00:29:12,670 --> 00:29:18,090
<i>I always tried to remember that,
when things didn't go my way.</i>

415
00:29:18,180 --> 00:29:20,100
Let's really get fired up now!

416
00:29:20,180 --> 00:29:25,230
-Get on your stand, Nixon!
- Twenty-eight, 44!

417
00:29:36,650 --> 00:29:39,410
- What's Nixon doing here?
- He thinks he can make it.

418
00:29:39,490 --> 00:29:41,990
Four years of being a tackling dummy.
Poor guy.

419
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:45,080
- All right! Let's go, defense!
- Hike!

420
00:29:49,420 --> 00:29:54,130
Worst athlete I've ever seen.
But he's got guts.

421
00:29:57,170 --> 00:29:59,720
OK, let's go! Let's do it!

422
00:29:59,800 --> 00:30:04,010
<i>In California's gubernatorial race,
Nixon returned to the political arena</i>

423
00:30:04,100 --> 00:30:09,310
<i>in a long and acrimonious bid against
popular incumbent Edmund G. Brown.</i>

424
00:30:09,390 --> 00:30:14,150
<i>Brown's campaign has benefited greatly
from the support of President Kennedy,</i>

425
00:30:14,230 --> 00:30:16,610
<i>while Nixon has had trouble
convincing voters</i>

426
00:30:16,690 --> 00:30:18,990
<i>this is not another run
for the presidency.</i>

427
00:30:19,070 --> 00:30:21,240
<i>With only a few precincts
left unreported,</i>

428
00:30:21,320 --> 00:30:21,950
<i>all indications are
of another defeat for Nixon,</i>

429
00:30:21,950 --> 00:30:23,870
<i>all indications are
of another defeat for Nixon,</i>

430
00:30:23,950 --> 00:30:28,160
<i>who lost the presidency just two
years ago by a paper-thin margin.</i>

431
00:30:28,250 --> 00:30:30,540
<i>It seems his brief political comeback</i>

432
00:30:30,620 --> 00:30:32,540
<i>- is in ruins.
- Making a statement?</i>

433
00:30:34,210 --> 00:30:36,460
Thank you, Fidel Castro.

434
00:30:36,550 --> 00:30:40,010
- You're not going to blame Castro?
- I sure am!

435
00:30:40,090 --> 00:30:43,180
Goddamn missile crisis united
the country behind Kennedy.

436
00:30:43,260 --> 00:30:45,850
He was supporting Brown.
People were scared.

437
00:30:45,930 --> 00:30:47,980
Castro staged this just to beat you.

438
00:30:48,060 --> 00:30:50,520
Before you join the jubilation
of my being beaten,

439
00:30:50,600 --> 00:30:52,810
remember people vote
not out of love but fear.

440
00:30:52,900 --> 00:30:58,240
They don't teach that at Sunday school
or the Whittier Community Playhouse.

441
00:30:58,320 --> 00:31:02,360
- I should go check in with our people.
- I'm glad they don't, Dick.

442
00:31:02,450 --> 00:31:06,580
I'm glad they don't because life
is tough and it is unfair

443
00:31:06,660 --> 00:31:10,330
and sometimes you forget
that in your self pity.

444
00:31:11,960 --> 00:31:16,750
You forget sometimes, Dick, that I had
a life before you, before California.

445
00:31:18,510 --> 00:31:20,510
Cocksucker!

446
00:31:23,970 --> 00:31:27,100
Don't you want to listen
to Governor Brown's victory speech?

447
00:31:27,180 --> 00:31:30,600
Nope. Not going to listen
to any more speeches ever again.

448
00:31:30,680 --> 00:31:32,640
Amen to that.

449
00:31:32,730 --> 00:31:33,850
It's over, Dick.

450
00:31:35,310 --> 00:31:38,280
- I'll concede in the morning.
- Not that.

451
00:31:47,870 --> 00:31:49,160
Buddy?

452
00:32:08,850 --> 00:32:10,640
I have always stood by you.

453
00:32:10,720 --> 00:32:14,310
I campaigned for you
when I was pregnant.

454
00:32:14,390 --> 00:32:18,190
During Checkers, when Ike
wanted you out, I told you to fight.

455
00:32:19,900 --> 00:32:22,650
This is different, Dick.

456
00:32:22,740 --> 00:32:24,200
You've changed.

457
00:32:26,200 --> 00:32:30,160
You've grown more bitter,
like you're at war with the world.

458
00:32:30,240 --> 00:32:32,250
You weren't that way before.

459
00:32:34,410 --> 00:32:37,630
I'm 50 years old now, Dick.

460
00:32:37,710 --> 00:32:40,460
How many millions of miles
have I traveled?

461
00:32:40,550 --> 00:32:44,170
How many millions of peoples' hands
have I shaked I just don't like?

462
00:32:44,260 --> 00:32:47,890
How many thank-you notes have I written?

463
00:32:47,970 --> 00:32:51,140
It's as if I, I don't know,
just went to sleep a long time ago

464
00:32:51,220 --> 00:32:53,430
and missed the years between.

465
00:32:55,940 --> 00:32:57,480
I've had enough.

466
00:33:00,150 --> 00:33:03,320
What are you saying?
What are you talking about?

467
00:33:05,400 --> 00:33:06,910
I want a divorce.

468
00:33:08,660 --> 00:33:12,990
My God. Divorce?
What about the girls?

469
00:33:15,120 --> 00:33:20,130
The girls'll grow up. They only
know you from television anyway.

470
00:33:20,210 --> 00:33:23,380
- It'll ruin us, our family.
- No, you're ruining us.

471
00:33:23,460 --> 00:33:26,050
If we stay with you,
you'll take us down with you.

472
00:33:26,130 --> 00:33:28,300
This isn't political.
This is our life.

473
00:33:28,390 --> 00:33:29,850
Everything's political.

474
00:33:29,930 --> 00:33:33,520
- I'm political, you're political.
- No, I'm not. I'm finished.

475
00:33:40,310 --> 00:33:42,730
Well, this is just
what they want, Buddy.

476
00:33:44,150 --> 00:33:45,610
Don't you see?

477
00:33:48,910 --> 00:33:52,490
They want to drive us apart, to beat us.

478
00:33:52,580 --> 00:33:55,580
We can't let them do it.

479
00:33:55,660 --> 00:33:57,710
We've been through too much together.

480
00:33:57,790 --> 00:34:00,080
We belong together.

481
00:34:00,170 --> 00:34:03,340
That's what you said
the first time we met.

482
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:06,170
You didn't even know me.

483
00:34:07,220 --> 00:34:08,970
Oh, yes, I did.

484
00:34:12,010 --> 00:34:14,770
I asked you to marry me, didn't I?

485
00:34:14,850 --> 00:34:17,640
On our first date.

486
00:34:17,730 --> 00:34:21,020
I said it because I knew...

487
00:34:21,100 --> 00:34:23,690
I knew you were the one.

488
00:34:25,360 --> 00:34:27,570
So solid.

489
00:34:27,650 --> 00:34:30,110
So strong.

490
00:34:30,200 --> 00:34:32,410
- So beautiful.
- Hi, I'm Pat Ryan.

491
00:34:34,120 --> 00:34:37,080
- Richard Nixon.
- It's a pleasure to meet you.

492
00:34:37,160 --> 00:34:38,960
Pleasure to meet you.

493
00:34:55,220 --> 00:34:57,060
Well, in a way, yes.

494
00:34:57,140 --> 00:34:59,310
Don't tell me you've
been cutting my part.

495
00:34:59,390 --> 00:35:03,150
Of course, honey, you know I
would never deceive you. Don't you?

496
00:35:32,130 --> 00:35:34,890
You were the most beautiful thing
I'd ever seen.

497
00:35:37,600 --> 00:35:40,430
I don't want to lose you.

498
00:35:42,850 --> 00:35:45,810
- Ever.
- Dick, don't.

499
00:35:52,700 --> 00:35:54,610
You really want me to quit?

500
00:35:59,120 --> 00:36:01,290
We can be happy.

501
00:36:02,580 --> 00:36:04,620
We really can.

502
00:36:06,420 --> 00:36:09,130
The girls and I love you, Dick.

503
00:36:12,970 --> 00:36:15,180
And if I stop,

504
00:36:15,260 --> 00:36:19,060
there'll be no more talk of divorce?

505
00:36:28,060 --> 00:36:31,570
I'll do it. No more.

506
00:36:34,200 --> 00:36:35,820
Are you serious?

507
00:36:37,200 --> 00:36:39,700
Yeah. I'm out.

508
00:36:41,200 --> 00:36:42,750
Is that the truth?

509
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:49,840
I'll never run again. I promise.

510
00:36:52,340 --> 00:36:53,760
Yeah.

511
00:36:57,090 --> 00:36:58,890
I love you, Buddy.

512
00:37:00,010 --> 00:37:01,140
I love you.

513
00:37:02,220 --> 00:37:04,020
I love you.

514
00:37:07,060 --> 00:37:08,560
Where are they?

515
00:37:08,650 --> 00:37:13,110
- You don't have to make a statement.
- No!

516
00:37:13,190 --> 00:37:18,070
Gentlemen, I can tell you Mr. Nixon
is a man who is graceful in defeat,

517
00:37:18,160 --> 00:37:20,080
and if he was here with us...

518
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:27,460
Can I have some quiet, please?

519
00:37:30,040 --> 00:37:32,170
Give the... Just a second!

520
00:37:32,250 --> 00:37:34,880
Some quiet, please. Quiet!

521
00:37:36,010 --> 00:37:37,470
Thank you!

522
00:37:38,470 --> 00:37:40,640
- Mr. Nixon!
- Uh... Ahem.

523
00:37:40,720 --> 00:37:45,230
I believe Governor Brown has a heart,

524
00:37:45,310 --> 00:37:48,810
even though he believes I do not.

525
00:37:48,900 --> 00:37:51,980
I believe he's a good American,

526
00:37:52,070 --> 00:37:54,650
even though he feels I am not.

527
00:37:54,730 --> 00:37:59,990
I'm proud of the fact that I
defended my opponent's patriotism.

528
00:38:00,820 --> 00:38:05,410
You gentlemen didn't report it,
but I'm proud I did that. And...

529
00:38:05,500 --> 00:38:08,000
And I would appreciate,
for once, gentlemen,

530
00:38:08,080 --> 00:38:10,710
if you would just print what I say.

531
00:38:12,090 --> 00:38:15,340
For 16 years, uh,
ever since the Hiss case,

532
00:38:15,420 --> 00:38:18,840
you've had a lot of fun. A lot of fun.

533
00:38:18,930 --> 00:38:22,350
But recognize you have a responsibility,

534
00:38:22,430 --> 00:38:25,850
if you're against the candidate,
to give him the shaft.

535
00:38:25,930 --> 00:38:29,600
But if you do that, at least put
one lonely reporter on the campaign

536
00:38:29,690 --> 00:38:34,190
who will report
what the candidate says now and then.

537
00:38:34,270 --> 00:38:39,240
I think, all in all,
I've given as good as I've taken.

538
00:38:39,320 --> 00:38:41,070
But as I leave you, I...

539
00:38:41,160 --> 00:38:46,040
I want you to know,
just think what you're gonna be missing.

540
00:38:46,950 --> 00:38:49,410
You won't have Nixon
to kick around anymore.

541
00:38:49,500 --> 00:38:51,290
Kick around anymore.

542
00:38:58,970 --> 00:39:00,630
Uh...

543
00:39:01,590 --> 00:39:05,060
Because, gentlemen,
this is my last press conference.

544
00:39:05,140 --> 00:39:08,730
- Thank you and good day.
- Is this the end of politics for you?

545
00:39:13,440 --> 00:39:14,860
Will you run again?

546
00:39:18,690 --> 00:39:22,780
<i>In California, we can
officially write the political obituary</i>

547
00:39:22,860 --> 00:39:26,080
<i>of Richard Milhous Nixon.
A small town lawyer like Lincoln,</i>

548
00:39:26,160 --> 00:39:29,910
<i>Nixon became a representative at 33
and a senator at 35,</i>

549
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:33,370
<i>as part of the postwar Republican sweep
of the congressional elections</i>

550
00:39:33,460 --> 00:39:36,340
<i>that attacked FDR's
big-government New Deal.</i>

551
00:39:36,420 --> 00:39:38,920
<i>Running as
a South Pacific veteran,</i>

552
00:39:39,010 --> 00:39:41,170
<i>victories over
Congressman Jerry Voorhis</i>

553
00:39:41,260 --> 00:39:44,590
<i>and Senator Helen Gahagan Douglas
made it clear that, to Nixon,</i>

554
00:39:44,680 --> 00:39:48,600
<i>politics was war. He didn't
have opponents, he had enemies.</i>

555
00:39:48,680 --> 00:39:50,980
Why, she's pink,
right down to her underwear!

556
00:39:51,060 --> 00:39:53,900
<i>Nixon became one of the
leading lights on the notorious</i>

557
00:39:53,980 --> 00:39:57,610
<i>House Un-American Activities Committee,
questioning labor leaders,</i>

558
00:39:57,690 --> 00:40:00,650
<i>Spanish Civil War veterans,
Hollywood celebrities.</i>

559
00:40:00,740 --> 00:40:04,160
<i>- They'd all be sent back to Russia.
- But it was the Alger Hiss case</i>

560
00:40:04,240 --> 00:40:06,120
<i>that made Nixon a household name.</i>

561
00:40:06,200 --> 00:40:08,240
<i>One of the architects
of the United Nations,</i>

562
00:40:08,330 --> 00:40:10,700
<i>intimate of FDR
and Oliver Wendell Holmes,</i>

563
00:40:10,790 --> 00:40:13,370
<i>Alger Hiss was
a State Department diplomat</i>

564
00:40:13,460 --> 00:40:16,210
<i>accused by freelance journalist
Whittaker Chambers</i>

565
00:40:16,290 --> 00:40:18,880
<i>of passing secret documents
to the Soviet Union.</i>

566
00:40:18,960 --> 00:40:21,420
<i>- Hiss is lying.
- Hiss claimed he was being set up</i>

567
00:40:21,510 --> 00:40:25,010
<i>by Nixon and J. Edgar Hoover
to discredit the New Deal's policies.</i>

568
00:40:25,090 --> 00:40:30,100
<i>I am not, and never have been,
a member of the Communist party.</i>

569
00:40:30,180 --> 00:40:32,930
<i>The case came down
to an Underwood typewriter</i>

570
00:40:33,020 --> 00:40:36,230
<i>and a roll of film hidden
in a pumpkin patch.</i>

571
00:40:37,230 --> 00:40:41,820
<i>I asked Hiss if he'd known Chambers.
When he said no, I knew he was lying.</i>

572
00:40:41,900 --> 00:40:43,150
<i>I knew I had him.</i>

573
00:40:43,240 --> 00:40:47,240
<i>After two trials, Hiss was
convicted not of spying but of perjury.</i>

574
00:40:47,320 --> 00:40:49,990
<i>To some, Nixon was a hero and a patriot.</i>

575
00:40:50,080 --> 00:40:53,080
<i>But to many, he was a self-promoter.</i>

576
00:40:53,160 --> 00:40:55,290
<i>Eleanor Roosevelt
angrily condemned him.</i>

577
00:40:55,370 --> 00:40:59,670
<i>Nixon continued to tear into Truman,
Acheson and the Democratic party</i>

578
00:40:59,750 --> 00:41:02,340
<i>for losing mainland China in 1949,</i>

579
00:41:02,420 --> 00:41:05,840
<i>and blamed the Korean War
on a weak foreign policy.</i>

580
00:41:05,930 --> 00:41:09,600
<i>I promise to expose and to continue
to expose the people that have sold</i>

581
00:41:09,680 --> 00:41:13,140
<i>- this country down the river!
- His speeches, if more subtle</i>

582
00:41:13,220 --> 00:41:17,230
<i>than those of his Republican ally,
Joe McCarthy, were just as aggressive.</i>

583
00:41:18,400 --> 00:41:20,980
<i>The direct result
of Truman's decision</i>

584
00:41:21,070 --> 00:41:23,190
<i>is that China has gone Communist!</i>

585
00:41:23,280 --> 00:41:26,150
<i>Mao is a monster! Why?</i>

586
00:41:26,240 --> 00:41:29,530
<i>Who in the State Department
is watching over American interests?</i>

587
00:41:29,620 --> 00:41:31,830
<i>Who has given the Russians
the atomic bomb?</i>

588
00:41:31,910 --> 00:41:36,920
<i>The Soviet Union is an example of the
slave state in the ultimate development.</i>

589
00:41:37,750 --> 00:41:40,880
<i>Driven by demons that
seemed more personal than political,</i>

590
00:41:40,960 --> 00:41:45,970
<i>Nixon became Eisenhower's
vice presidential candidate in 1952.</i>

591
00:41:46,050 --> 00:41:48,050
<i>But then came the Checkers crisis.</i>

592
00:41:48,130 --> 00:41:51,050
<i>Nixon was accused
of hiding a secret slush fund.</i>

593
00:41:51,140 --> 00:41:54,640
<i>About to be kicked off the ticket
by Ike, he went live on television...</i>

594
00:41:54,720 --> 00:41:58,980
<i>- ...in an unprecedented appearance.
- ...give this television audience</i>

595
00:41:59,060 --> 00:42:02,070
<i>a complete financial history.
Everything I've earned...</i>

596
00:42:02,150 --> 00:42:04,690
<i>The list included their house,
their Oldsmobile,</i>

597
00:42:04,780 --> 00:42:08,860
<i>Pat's Republican cloth coat. And lastly,
in what was to become history,</i>

598
00:42:08,950 --> 00:42:12,030
<i>a sentimental gift
from a Texas businessman.</i>

599
00:42:12,120 --> 00:42:15,580
<i>You know what it was? It was a little
cocker spaniel dog in a crate</i>

600
00:42:15,660 --> 00:42:17,870
<i>that he'd sent
all the way from Texas,</i>

601
00:42:17,960 --> 00:42:21,210
<i>black and white, spotted.
And our little girl Tricia,</i>

602
00:42:21,290 --> 00:42:23,290
<i>the six-year-old, named it Checkers.</i>

603
00:42:23,380 --> 00:42:27,260
<i>- Fifty-eight million people saw it.
- Like all kids, they love the dog.</i>

604
00:42:27,340 --> 00:42:30,550
<i>It was shameless. It was manipulative.</i>

605
00:42:30,640 --> 00:42:33,720
<i>Regardless of what they say about him,
we're gonna keep him.</i>

606
00:42:33,810 --> 00:42:35,850
<i>It was a huge success.</i>

607
00:42:36,640 --> 00:42:40,100
<i>He stayed on the national scene,
serving two terms as vice president</i>

608
00:42:40,190 --> 00:42:44,360
<i>under Eisenhower, against Khrushchev
at the Kitchen Debate in Moscow</i>

609
00:42:44,440 --> 00:42:50,240
<i>and stoned by Latin mobs in Venezuela.
Nixon once again became a national hero.</i>

610
00:42:50,320 --> 00:42:53,410
<i>But it all came to a crashing end
against Kennedy in 1960</i>

611
00:42:53,490 --> 00:42:57,080
<i>and Pat Brown in California in '62.</i>

612
00:42:57,160 --> 00:43:00,670
<i>And thus ends
a great American political story.</i>

613
00:43:00,750 --> 00:43:04,590
<i>The truth is we never knew
who Richard Nixon really was,</i>

614
00:43:04,670 --> 00:43:07,670
<i>and now that he is gone, we never will.</i>

615
00:43:15,640 --> 00:43:17,470
Poor little Tricia.

616
00:43:17,560 --> 00:43:21,230
I told her her daddy couldn't get a job
in this city when he got out of Duke.

617
00:43:21,310 --> 00:43:25,020
Every white-shoe lawyer firm turned
me down. Didn't have the right look.

618
00:43:25,110 --> 00:43:27,650
- I couldn't even get into the FBI.
- Hi! How are ya?

619
00:43:27,730 --> 00:43:30,900
Did you catch that picture of you
in the news last week, Dick?

620
00:43:30,990 --> 00:43:33,780
- You were standin' on Fifth Avenue.
- Oh, yeah.

621
00:43:33,870 --> 00:43:37,870
You were lookin' straight ahead and
everyone else was lookin' the other way,

622
00:43:37,950 --> 00:43:41,370
- like you just farted or somethin'.

623
00:43:41,460 --> 00:43:45,340
It said, "Who remembers Dick Nixon?"

624
00:43:45,420 --> 00:43:48,170
Unbelievable. I was screamin'.

625
00:43:48,250 --> 00:43:50,210
Yeah, that was hilarious, Martha.

626
00:43:50,300 --> 00:43:53,970
They were looking the other direction,
waiting for the light to change.

627
00:43:54,050 --> 00:43:56,600
Typical of the press,
they wouldn't correct it.

628
00:43:56,680 --> 00:43:59,350
I think we oughta catch Rocky
before he leaves.

629
00:43:59,430 --> 00:44:02,140
I'm sure it's just a little
run of bad luck, Mr. Nixon.

630
00:44:02,230 --> 00:44:05,150
- He can walk this direction, can't he?
- Oh, I don't know.

631
00:44:05,230 --> 00:44:08,940
- I've read some nice things about you.
- Maybe where you come from.

632
00:44:09,030 --> 00:44:13,780
But where I come from, Dick Nixon is
as misunderstood as a fox in a henhouse.

633
00:44:13,860 --> 00:44:17,030
And do you know why?
Because, my darlin',

634
00:44:17,120 --> 00:44:19,370
they all think that
your smile and your face

635
00:44:19,450 --> 00:44:22,750
are never in the same place
at the same time.

636
00:44:22,830 --> 00:44:25,630
You and me, we're gonna
have to work on that, sweetie.

637
00:44:25,710 --> 00:44:28,380
Someone freshen Martha's drink.
She's down a quart.

638
00:44:28,460 --> 00:44:31,050
Well, zip-a-dee-doo-dah!

639
00:44:31,130 --> 00:44:35,390
- I think he is frightened by my charm.
- I know I am.

640
00:44:35,470 --> 00:44:38,890
- Pat can't stand her.
- It's the thing she does.

641
00:44:38,970 --> 00:44:41,890
- She talks at night.
- Talks all day too.

642
00:44:41,970 --> 00:44:44,060
How the hell can you
put up with her, John?

643
00:44:44,140 --> 00:44:47,980
Well, I'm in love with her.
And she's great in bed.

644
00:44:49,320 --> 00:44:52,650
If a Rockefeller can't
become president of the United States,

645
00:44:52,740 --> 00:44:54,570
then what is the point of democracy?

646
00:44:54,650 --> 00:44:58,530
The point of democracy is that even the
son of a grocer can become president.

647
00:44:58,620 --> 00:45:00,910
And you came damn close, Dick.
How are you?

648
00:45:00,990 --> 00:45:03,580
Hi, John.
New York treating you all right?

649
00:45:03,660 --> 00:45:05,830
I'm sorry I haven't
been able to see you.

650
00:45:05,920 --> 00:45:09,090
- You're looking happy, Rocky.
- Happy. Happy, Dick Nixon.

651
00:45:09,170 --> 00:45:11,250
- You remember him.
- Nice to see you again.

652
00:45:11,340 --> 00:45:16,840
- You're obviously making him happy.
- Oh! Repartee, Dick! That's marvelous!

653
00:45:16,930 --> 00:45:21,260
What you predicting? Your boy
Goldwater gonna split the party?

654
00:45:21,350 --> 00:45:24,020
- Some say you are, Rocky.
- Let me tell you something.

655
00:45:24,100 --> 00:45:28,770
Every time the Republican party is a
home to extremism, we lose the election.

656
00:45:28,860 --> 00:45:31,150
- You oughta know better than anybody.
- Yeah.

657
00:45:31,230 --> 00:45:33,940
This guy Goldwater
is as stupid as McCarthy.

658
00:45:34,030 --> 00:45:38,030
And McCarthy never did you any good
in the long run, now, did he?

659
00:45:38,110 --> 00:45:39,870
That's right.

660
00:45:40,870 --> 00:45:46,580
- I hate these cocktail parties.
- John, I'm in hell.

661
00:45:46,660 --> 00:45:50,790
I'll be mentally dead in two years
and physically dead in four.

662
00:45:50,880 --> 00:45:55,970
Make some money, Dick.
Prove yourself to the Wall Street crowd.

663
00:45:56,050 --> 00:45:59,640
Let Goldwater and Rockefeller
take the fall against Kennedy.

664
00:45:59,720 --> 00:46:02,140
I don't know.
I miss making love to the people.

665
00:46:02,220 --> 00:46:04,350
I miss entering a room.

666
00:46:04,430 --> 00:46:08,600
I miss the pure acting of it, John.

667
00:46:10,100 --> 00:46:12,360
I gotta get back in the arena.

668
00:46:15,900 --> 00:46:18,400
Ladies and gentlemen, it's showtime!

669
00:46:18,490 --> 00:46:22,490
Come on up.
Right this way, ladies and gentlemen.

670
00:46:22,580 --> 00:46:26,910
It's for you, it's for me.
It's Studebaker for 1963.

671
00:46:28,080 --> 00:46:31,830
Amen. Bless you for being here.
There's a man that loves Studebakers.

672
00:46:31,920 --> 00:46:35,090
- Can I get your autograph?
- Mr. Nixon, please run again.

673
00:46:35,170 --> 00:46:38,470
The ex-vice president of the United
States, Richard M. Nixon!

674
00:46:40,800 --> 00:46:44,970
- You throw a hell of a party, Jack.
- The party ain't even started yet.

675
00:46:45,060 --> 00:46:48,350
I've asked these gals out to the ranch
for a little private thing.

676
00:46:48,430 --> 00:46:51,150
We're gonna have some fun,
I guarantee ya.

677
00:46:51,230 --> 00:46:53,860
And there's some fellas
I'd really like you to meet.

678
00:46:53,940 --> 00:46:57,940
Trini and I got an early plane. We're
hoping to be back in New York for...

679
00:46:58,030 --> 00:47:03,120
It'll be OK. These guys are interesting.
And quiet. The girls are too.

680
00:47:03,200 --> 00:47:06,370
It's not often us Texans
get an opportunity to entertain

681
00:47:06,450 --> 00:47:08,790
- the future president.
- Here.

682
00:47:08,870 --> 00:47:11,210
Like you said, Jack,
I'm just a New York lawyer.

683
00:47:11,290 --> 00:47:14,420
- We'll see about that.
- Mr. Nixon, are you gonna run again?

684
00:47:14,500 --> 00:47:16,750
- I don't know.
- He will! I guarantee it!

685
00:47:22,300 --> 00:47:24,550
- Name it, baby.
- That little convertible?

686
00:47:24,640 --> 00:47:27,100
I'll buy you a diamond ring.
I'll buy you one.

687
00:47:27,180 --> 00:47:28,770
- Thank you.
- Hello, baby.

688
00:47:28,850 --> 00:47:30,890
Hey, wait, wait, wait.

689
00:47:30,980 --> 00:47:35,400
This is Julie there.
And that's Tricia.

690
00:47:35,480 --> 00:47:40,240
- Oh, yeah.
- She reminds me a bit of you, Sandy.

691
00:47:40,320 --> 00:47:44,370
She really is wholesome.
But, um, what about you?

692
00:47:44,450 --> 00:47:47,830
- What do you like?
- Well, I like music.

693
00:47:47,910 --> 00:47:51,910
- I like jazz.
- Jazz, yeah. Guy Lombardo.

694
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:53,370
How about rock and roll?

695
00:47:53,460 --> 00:47:55,880
- Elvis Presley?
- Yeah, he's good. Yeah.

696
00:47:55,960 --> 00:47:58,420
- Decent guy.
- Well, I guess,

697
00:47:58,500 --> 00:48:03,050
for me, it also depends on
what I'm doin' to the music, Dick.

698
00:48:04,340 --> 00:48:08,430
- Yeah.
- So, what's it like bein' so famous?

699
00:48:08,510 --> 00:48:10,680
A vice president!

700
00:48:10,770 --> 00:48:14,230
Well, it's, uh, not like that, Sandy.

701
00:48:15,520 --> 00:48:18,730
You see, the reason I got
into politics in the first place was,

702
00:48:18,820 --> 00:48:22,280
well, to do something for the people.

703
00:48:22,360 --> 00:48:26,280
So, how are you two doing?

704
00:48:26,370 --> 00:48:30,290
You know, Dick, there's more privacy
in the back of the...

705
00:48:30,370 --> 00:48:35,120
- No, Trini, we're fine here.
- OK.

706
00:48:35,210 --> 00:48:39,630
Hell, Kennedy just pissed Cuba away
to the Russians. Just pissed it away.

707
00:48:39,710 --> 00:48:43,630
And he doesn't know what the hell
he's doin' in Vietnam.

708
00:48:43,720 --> 00:48:46,300
These are dangerous times,
especially for business.

709
00:48:46,390 --> 00:48:50,640
- Agreed.
- We know what you tried to do for Cuba.

710
00:48:50,720 --> 00:48:54,560
If you had been elected in '60,
Castro would be dead now.

711
00:49:00,320 --> 00:49:03,400
Gentlemen, I tried.
I told Kennedy to go into Cuba.

712
00:49:03,490 --> 00:49:07,280
He heard me and he made his decision.
I appreciate your sentiments.

713
00:49:07,370 --> 00:49:10,080
I've heard them
from many fine Cuban patriots.

714
00:49:10,160 --> 00:49:12,660
But it's nothing
I can do anything about.

715
00:49:13,910 --> 00:49:18,000
It's a long drive to Dallas. Trini and I
have a plane to catch tomorrow. So...

716
00:49:18,080 --> 00:49:21,750
- Dick, these boys want you to run.
- Absolutely.

717
00:49:21,840 --> 00:49:24,090
- That's right.
- Now, they're serious.

718
00:49:24,170 --> 00:49:27,340
They can deliver the South
and put Texas in your column.

719
00:49:27,430 --> 00:49:29,010
They would have done it in '60.

720
00:49:29,100 --> 00:49:32,260
Only if Kennedy dumps Johnson.
That'll never happen.

721
00:49:32,350 --> 00:49:35,980
I don't think you know how much
people hate Kennedy down here.

722
00:49:36,060 --> 00:49:40,360
He's comin' to town tomorrow, and they
will run his ass outta town on a rail!

723
00:49:40,440 --> 00:49:42,690
- Damn right.
- That we will.

724
00:49:42,780 --> 00:49:46,950
We are willing to give you a shit pot
full of money to get rid of him.

725
00:49:47,030 --> 00:49:48,740
More than you ever dreamed of.

726
00:49:51,990 --> 00:49:56,620
Nobody's gonna beat Kennedy in '64
with all the money in the world.

727
00:50:00,290 --> 00:50:04,130
Suppose Kennedy don't run in '64.

728
00:50:05,460 --> 00:50:06,630
Not a chance.

729
00:50:09,140 --> 00:50:10,720
Yeah.

730
00:50:11,930 --> 00:50:16,140
Well, gentlemen, I promised my wife I...
I'm out of politics.

731
00:50:16,230 --> 00:50:20,600
You just came down here for the weather,
is that right, Mr. Nixon?

732
00:50:20,690 --> 00:50:24,900
I came down here
to close a deal for Studebaker.

733
00:50:24,980 --> 00:50:29,070
- What about '68, Dick?
- Five years, Trini.

734
00:50:29,160 --> 00:50:31,700
In politics, that's an eternity.

735
00:50:31,780 --> 00:50:36,580
Dick... your country needs you.

736
00:50:36,660 --> 00:50:39,870
Unfortunately, the country's
not available right now.

737
00:51:01,600 --> 00:51:06,360
President Kennedy's due in
from Fort Worth in about an hour.

738
00:51:06,440 --> 00:51:09,990
- Kennedy is due in from Fort Worth.
- Yeah, I know.

739
00:51:10,070 --> 00:51:12,320
OK. Let's go through here.

740
00:51:12,410 --> 00:51:14,780
- Excuse us.
- Excuse me. Coming through.

741
00:51:14,870 --> 00:51:17,240
- Excuse us.
- Thank you.

742
00:51:17,330 --> 00:51:21,250
Step away from the gate there.
Thank you.

743
00:51:26,960 --> 00:51:29,720
Go find the pilot.
Let's get out of here.

744
00:52:13,380 --> 00:52:16,760
Look, Edgar, these, uh...
these guys were really strange.

745
00:52:16,850 --> 00:52:19,970
<i>- You know, extremists.
- What do you mean by "strange"?</i>

746
00:52:20,060 --> 00:52:22,060
<i>- Right-wing stuff.
- Birchers?</i>

747
00:52:22,140 --> 00:52:24,730
<i>- Birchers, yeah.
- This thing's pretty straight.</i>

748
00:52:24,810 --> 00:52:28,860
<i>- In Dallas, Lee Harvey Oswald...
- Oswald's got a Cuba connection?</i>

749
00:52:28,940 --> 00:52:32,190
<i>- To Castro?
- ...maximum security facility.</i>

750
00:52:32,280 --> 00:52:34,910
<i>- Mrs. Kennedy...
- He's a real Communist.</i>

751
00:52:34,990 --> 00:52:37,200
Well, that makes sense.

752
00:52:37,280 --> 00:52:39,990
OK, well, thank you, Edgar.

753
00:52:41,540 --> 00:52:46,290
<i>Senator Ted Kennedy, arriving early
this morning with his mother and sister.</i>

754
00:52:46,380 --> 00:52:52,130
Hoover says this Oswald
checks out as a beatnik,

755
00:52:52,210 --> 00:52:55,840
- a real bum.
- Dick, you should call Bobby.

756
00:52:55,930 --> 00:52:58,890
He doesn't want me at the funeral.

757
00:52:58,970 --> 00:53:02,140
- You don't have to go.
- De Gaulle's gonna be there.

758
00:53:02,220 --> 00:53:07,730
<i>- McMillan. Adenauer.
- We go now to the rotunda...</i>

759
00:53:07,810 --> 00:53:10,400
Nixon can't not be there.

760
00:53:10,480 --> 00:53:14,490
Then call him.
I'm sure it was an oversight.

761
00:53:14,570 --> 00:53:18,240
<i>- Yeah.
- ...to pay their respects...</i>

762
00:53:18,320 --> 00:53:21,620
<i>- Jesus.
- ...to their fallen leader.</i>

763
00:53:21,700 --> 00:53:23,910
It's awful.

764
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:27,670
- It's an awful thing for this country.
- Dick?

765
00:53:29,500 --> 00:53:31,960
No, it's his way.

766
00:53:32,050 --> 00:53:34,090
He hates me.

767
00:53:34,170 --> 00:53:36,760
He and Teddy.

768
00:53:36,840 --> 00:53:38,760
They always hated me.

769
00:53:38,840 --> 00:53:43,140
They've lost their brother.
You know what that means, Dick.

770
00:53:44,180 --> 00:53:48,060
<i>These are perhaps the last
images of him alive with his family.</i>

771
00:53:51,520 --> 00:53:54,190
Please, make it stop!

772
00:53:55,740 --> 00:53:58,070
Hold him tighter.
Hold him tighter.

773
00:53:59,950 --> 00:54:02,120
Hold him tighter. Hold him tighter.

774
00:54:03,200 --> 00:54:06,410
Daddy, please make it stop!

775
00:54:06,500 --> 00:54:08,170
Hold him tighter.

776
00:54:08,250 --> 00:54:10,460
The infection's spread to his spine.

777
00:54:12,630 --> 00:54:13,960
Come on!

778
00:54:31,980 --> 00:54:33,070
Stop it!

779
00:54:34,530 --> 00:54:36,860
Get off!

780
00:54:56,510 --> 00:54:58,050
You're it!

781
00:55:08,520 --> 00:55:10,770
No. No, don't!

782
00:55:19,490 --> 00:55:22,490
If I'd been president,
they never would've killed me.

783
00:55:25,280 --> 00:55:28,540
<i>Vice President Johnson,
shown here being sworn in...</i>

784
00:55:28,620 --> 00:55:31,790
- Dick, are you gonna call? Bobby.
- Hmm?

785
00:55:36,090 --> 00:55:39,300
I'll go through Johnson.
We'll be invited.

786
00:55:45,220 --> 00:55:48,970
<i>This is a sad time
for all people.</i>

787
00:55:49,060 --> 00:55:51,890
<i>I ask for your help.</i>

788
00:55:51,980 --> 00:55:55,360
<i>...and are going
to see Vietnam through</i>

789
00:55:55,440 --> 00:55:57,820
<i>to an honorable peace...</i>

790
00:56:01,280 --> 00:56:04,280
<i>...to defend an honored cause,</i>

791
00:56:04,360 --> 00:56:07,410
<i>whatever the price,
whatever the burden...</i>

792
00:56:07,490 --> 00:56:13,420
<i>...whatever the sacrifice
that duty may require.</i>

793
00:56:13,500 --> 00:56:18,710
<i>Accordingly... I shall not seek...</i>

794
00:56:20,210 --> 00:56:22,760
<i>...and I will not accept...</i>

795
00:56:22,840 --> 00:56:26,970
<i>...the nomination of my party
for another term as your president.</i>

796
00:56:28,930 --> 00:56:32,810
<i>Good night, and God bless all of you.</i>

797
00:56:34,690 --> 00:56:37,520
<i>Johnson's withdrawal
resurrects Richard Nixon</i>

798
00:56:37,610 --> 00:56:41,110
<i>as a strong Republican candidate
with a secret plan to end the war.</i>

799
00:56:41,190 --> 00:56:44,450
<i>His mother, Hannah Nixon,
just before her death last year,</i>

800
00:56:44,530 --> 00:56:47,200
<i>commented on her son's chances.</i>

801
00:56:47,280 --> 00:56:52,790
Mrs. Nixon, do you think your son
will ever return to politics?

802
00:56:52,870 --> 00:56:56,000
I don't think he has a choice.

803
00:56:56,080 --> 00:56:58,920
He has always been a leader.

804
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:03,550
Do you think he'd make
a great president, Mrs. Nixon?

805
00:57:03,630 --> 00:57:06,800
If he's on God's side, yes.

806
00:57:07,890 --> 00:57:10,430
You must be very proud of your son.

807
00:57:10,510 --> 00:57:13,730
I have always been proud
of all of my children.

808
00:57:17,560 --> 00:57:20,150
Of course,
no one can see into the future.

809
00:57:20,230 --> 00:57:22,480
We didn't know this day would come.

810
00:57:22,570 --> 00:57:25,070
- Where'd he go?
- In the side door.

811
00:57:25,150 --> 00:57:28,070
- Is that Mitchell?
- Shit! Missed him.

812
00:57:29,580 --> 00:57:32,740
I thought that guy was gonna
kiss your hand on the side of it.

813
00:57:32,830 --> 00:57:35,000
- Congratulations, sir.
- Yeah, thanks.

814
00:57:35,080 --> 00:57:38,040
Jesus, Dick!
I've never seen anything like it.

815
00:57:38,130 --> 00:57:40,630
Even the goddamn Times
is saying you've got it.

816
00:57:40,710 --> 00:57:43,880
- Vietnam's gonna put you in there.
- We got the press this time.

817
00:57:43,960 --> 00:57:48,680
- We got the big mo. We're back.
- So you've decided.

818
00:57:52,180 --> 00:57:54,220
Were you planning to tell me?

819
00:57:55,770 --> 00:57:58,900
We haven't announced
anything yet, but...

820
00:58:00,900 --> 00:58:03,110
Jesus. Uh... Pat?

821
00:58:05,990 --> 00:58:09,030
Uh, wait in the living room,
will you, fellas? What is it, John?

822
00:58:09,110 --> 00:58:12,700
You need her, Dick. In '60,
she was worth five, six million votes.

823
00:58:12,780 --> 00:58:16,370
Yeah. Don't worry.
I'll use the old Nixon charm.

824
00:58:17,750 --> 00:58:19,960
In there. OK.

825
00:58:21,000 --> 00:58:22,290
Who could resist that?

826
00:58:27,760 --> 00:58:29,300
Buddy?

827
00:58:32,140 --> 00:58:33,560
You should be going.

828
00:58:33,640 --> 00:58:36,520
Primaries are soon,
aren't they? New Hampshire.

829
00:58:36,600 --> 00:58:39,230
I love you, Buddy. I need you.

830
00:58:39,310 --> 00:58:41,770
I don't want them to love me.

831
00:58:41,860 --> 00:58:44,820
But I need you out there.

832
00:58:44,900 --> 00:58:49,910
It won't be like the last time.
The war's crippled the Democrats.

833
00:58:49,990 --> 00:58:52,570
I can win. We deserve it.

834
00:58:52,660 --> 00:58:55,740
It's ours, Buddy, at last.

835
00:58:55,830 --> 00:58:59,080
Nobody knows that better than you.

836
00:58:59,160 --> 00:59:01,170
Frank Nixon's boy.

837
00:59:01,250 --> 00:59:05,420
Do you remember what Mom said?
We're not like other people. We...

838
00:59:05,500 --> 00:59:07,630
We don't choose our way.

839
00:59:08,670 --> 00:59:10,930
We can really change things, Buddy.

840
00:59:11,010 --> 00:59:14,600
We got a chance to get it right.
We can change America.

841
00:59:14,680 --> 00:59:18,310
It was our dream, Buddy,
together, always.

842
00:59:20,270 --> 00:59:24,440
- Do you really want this, Dick?
- Yeah. This, above all.

843
00:59:24,520 --> 00:59:29,820
- And then you'll be happy?
- Yeah, you know I will. Yes! I will.

844
00:59:30,900 --> 00:59:32,990
Then I'll be there for you.

845
00:59:33,070 --> 00:59:35,950
And we are gonna win this time.
I can feel it.

846
00:59:36,030 --> 00:59:37,540
Yeah!

847
00:59:38,580 --> 00:59:41,460
You're the strongest woman
I ever met, Buddy.

848
00:59:41,540 --> 00:59:44,630
- Can I just ask for one thing?
- Anything.

849
00:59:44,710 --> 00:59:47,130
- Would you kiss me?
- Yeah!

850
00:59:54,510 --> 00:59:56,810
We're gonna win the race.

851
00:59:58,560 --> 01:00:02,810
<i>My thanks. It's on to Chicago
and let's win there. Thank you.</i>

852
01:00:02,890 --> 01:00:05,810
I would never question
Senator Kennedy's patriotism.

853
01:00:05,900 --> 01:00:09,650
But going around the country,
promising peace at any price

854
01:00:09,740 --> 01:00:12,570
is, uh, exactly what the
North Vietnamese want to hear.

855
01:00:12,650 --> 01:00:14,110
Cue the crowd.

856
01:00:16,030 --> 01:00:18,540
Go to this bald guy.
Yeah, he's great, isn't he?

857
01:00:19,660 --> 01:00:21,750
<i>I, unlike Senator Kennedy,</i>

858
01:00:21,830 --> 01:00:24,670
<i>have a plan to end the war immediately.</i>

859
01:00:24,750 --> 01:00:29,670
<i>But not for peace at any price,
but peace with honor.</i>

860
01:00:29,760 --> 01:00:33,630
What do you think this plan is, Edgar?
A nuclear attack?

861
01:00:33,720 --> 01:00:36,510
He's lying, Clyde. Always has.

862
01:00:36,600 --> 01:00:39,100
That's why Nixon's always been useful.

863
01:00:42,390 --> 01:00:44,100
Hold still.

864
01:00:44,190 --> 01:00:46,770
- OK, who's next?
- The Negro.

865
01:00:46,860 --> 01:00:49,480
No, we gotta have a Negro.
This guy right here.

866
01:00:49,570 --> 01:00:50,610
Negro, front row.

867
01:00:51,780 --> 01:00:55,030
- Mr. Nixon, sir.
- Yeah.

868
01:00:55,110 --> 01:00:58,030
We all know you have built your career

869
01:00:58,120 --> 01:01:01,040
on smearing people as Communists.

870
01:01:01,120 --> 01:01:03,870
And now you are building your campaign

871
01:01:03,960 --> 01:01:06,380
on the divisions in this country,

872
01:01:06,460 --> 01:01:09,960
stirring up hatred
and turning people against each other.

873
01:01:10,050 --> 01:01:13,220
- What the fuck's he doing? A speech!
- Cut him off.

874
01:01:13,300 --> 01:01:15,760
- I can't. This isn't Russia.
- Sounds like a Negro.

875
01:01:15,840 --> 01:01:19,470
- Saying Negro things. What's he doing?
- Sounded white when we screened.

876
01:01:19,550 --> 01:01:21,560
Doesn't sound white now,
sounds like Angela Davis.

877
01:01:21,640 --> 01:01:24,520
When are you gonna tell us
what you really stand for?

878
01:01:24,600 --> 01:01:27,060
- Go to commercial!
- There are no commercials.

879
01:01:27,150 --> 01:01:29,190
- You bought the whole half hour.
- Shit!

880
01:01:29,270 --> 01:01:33,570
When are you going to take off that mask
and show us who you really are?

881
01:01:33,650 --> 01:01:34,860
Shut up and sit down!

882
01:01:34,950 --> 01:01:37,450
- OK. OK.
- It's a high hard one, chief.

883
01:01:37,530 --> 01:01:39,990
- Park it.
- There are divisions in this country.

884
01:01:40,080 --> 01:01:43,750
- That's because you created them.
- I did not. The Democrats did.

885
01:01:43,830 --> 01:01:46,540
If it's dialogue you want,
you're more likely to get it from me

886
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:49,250
than from people burning down cities.
Just think about it.

887
01:01:49,330 --> 01:01:51,550
- Dr. King said the same thing.
- Oh, please.

888
01:01:51,630 --> 01:01:54,590
You know, young man,
who a great hero is? Abraham Lincoln.

889
01:01:54,670 --> 01:01:57,220
- Abraham Lincoln.
- Lincoln. Is he beautiful?

890
01:01:57,300 --> 01:02:00,350
He believed in common ground.
He brought this country together.

891
01:02:01,680 --> 01:02:03,560
I love that man. I love him.

892
01:02:03,640 --> 01:02:07,020
I want the son of a bitch
who got that agitator in here fired!

893
01:02:07,100 --> 01:02:10,440
- I have another question.
- There's a little girl sitting here.

894
01:02:10,520 --> 01:02:13,820
- A little girl sitting with a sign.
- Bag the spook. Go to the girl.

895
01:02:13,900 --> 01:02:16,610
- Can you see the girl?
- There are three simple words:

896
01:02:16,700 --> 01:02:18,990
"Bring us together."
That is what I want,

897
01:02:19,070 --> 01:02:22,490
and that is what the great
silent majority of Americans want.

898
01:02:22,580 --> 01:02:27,120
And that is why I want to be president.
To bring us together.

899
01:02:27,210 --> 01:02:30,710
<i>- Give me a break, Mary.
- Now, you all know me. I'm one of you.</i>

900
01:02:30,790 --> 01:02:33,130
<i>I grew up here,
a stone's throw from here,</i>

901
01:02:33,210 --> 01:02:37,800
<i>- on a lemon ranch in Yorba Linda.
- Poorest lemon ranch in California.</i>

902
01:02:37,880 --> 01:02:40,930
<i>Poorest lemon ranch in California,
I can assure you of that.</i>

903
01:02:41,010 --> 01:02:44,930
<i>- My dad sold it before they found oil.
- My dad sold it before they found oil.</i>

904
01:02:45,020 --> 01:02:48,270
<i>- But it was all we had.
- But it was all we had.</i>

905
01:02:48,350 --> 01:02:53,230
<i>- My dad built the house with his hands.
- You're new here. What's your name?</i>

906
01:02:53,320 --> 01:02:55,280
Joaquin, Mr. Hoover.

907
01:02:56,230 --> 01:02:57,740
Oh.

908
01:02:58,450 --> 01:03:04,080
<i>My father sacrificed everything he had
so that his sons could go to college.</i>

909
01:03:04,160 --> 01:03:08,790
<i>- A gentle Quaker mother quietly wept
- Oh, Christ.</i>

910
01:03:08,870 --> 01:03:11,500
<i>- when he went to war.
- Turn this crap off, Clyde.</i>

911
01:03:11,580 --> 01:03:14,090
<i>- It's giving me a headache.
- A great teacher.</i>

