1000
01:09:32,960 --> 01:09:37,930
<i>Wherever there was need for, uh,
an executive action capability,</i>

1001
01:09:38,010 --> 01:09:40,140
<i>there's Track Two.</i>

1002
01:09:40,220 --> 01:09:45,310
In Cuba, Track One
was, uh, the Bay of Pigs invasion.

1003
01:09:45,390 --> 01:09:47,900
Track Two was our idea.

1004
01:09:47,980 --> 01:09:51,770
We thought that the invasion wouldn't
work unless we got rid of Castro.

1005
01:09:51,860 --> 01:09:57,570
So we asked ourselves, uh,
"Who else wants Castro dead?"

1006
01:09:57,660 --> 01:10:00,660
The Mafia or money people?

1007
01:10:00,740 --> 01:10:03,620
So we put together Track Two.

1008
01:10:17,220 --> 01:10:20,680
First assassination attempt was in '60.

1009
01:10:20,760 --> 01:10:24,430
- Just before the election.
- Before? Eisenhower approved that?

1010
01:10:24,520 --> 01:10:28,350
Yeah. Well, he didn't veto it.

1011
01:10:28,440 --> 01:10:31,440
I ran the White House side,

1012
01:10:31,520 --> 01:10:35,110
and the Mob contact was Johnny Roselli.

1013
01:10:35,190 --> 01:10:40,410
One of the CIA guys was this jackass,
Howard Hunt.

1014
01:10:40,490 --> 01:10:43,280
- Jesus.
- Yeah.

1015
01:10:43,370 --> 01:10:45,910
Not just Howard Hunt,
but Frank Sturgis

1016
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:50,080
and all those other Cubans.

1017
01:10:50,170 --> 01:10:52,090
All of them in the Watergate.

1018
01:10:54,460 --> 01:10:57,670
They're all involved in Cuba.

1019
01:11:02,550 --> 01:11:06,430
Yeah, Hunt reported to my military aide.

1020
01:11:06,520 --> 01:11:10,350
I don't know how much Hunt knows
or the Cubans, but...

1021
01:11:11,770 --> 01:11:13,690
...you never know.

1022
01:11:13,770 --> 01:11:17,740
So you wanted Castro dead.
Everybody wanted Castro dead.

1023
01:11:18,650 --> 01:11:22,370
You know, if Hunt
and the others are CIA...

1024
01:11:22,450 --> 01:11:26,080
...why don't we just dump this
back in the CIA's lap,

1025
01:11:26,160 --> 01:11:30,670
- let Dick Helms take the fall?
- Because...

1026
01:11:30,750 --> 01:11:34,420
Because Helms knows too much.

1027
01:11:35,590 --> 01:11:38,720
If there's anyone in this country
who knows more than me,

1028
01:11:38,800 --> 01:11:42,430
it's Hoover and Helms, and you
don't fuck with Dick Helms, period.

1029
01:11:42,510 --> 01:11:46,810
All right. But why,
if Kennedy was so clean in all this,

1030
01:11:46,890 --> 01:11:50,770
- didn't he cancel Track Two?
- 'Cause he didn't even know about it.

1031
01:11:52,690 --> 01:11:56,610
The CIA, uh, never told him.
They just kept it going.

1032
01:11:57,440 --> 01:12:00,240
It had a life of its own
like it was some...

1033
01:12:01,530 --> 01:12:04,530
...kind of a thing, you know?

1034
01:12:04,620 --> 01:12:06,580
It doesn't even know it exists.

1035
01:12:06,660 --> 01:12:10,540
It just eats people
when it doesn't need 'em anymore.

1036
01:12:10,620 --> 01:12:14,170
<i>Two days after the Bay of Pigs,</i>

1037
01:12:14,250 --> 01:12:18,550
<i>Kennedy called me
and he reamed me out.</i>

1038
01:12:18,630 --> 01:12:22,550
- He just found out about Track Two.
- You never told him?

1039
01:12:22,630 --> 01:12:25,470
I didn't want him to get the credit.

1040
01:12:26,600 --> 01:12:28,430
He said I'd stabbed him in the back

1041
01:12:28,510 --> 01:12:31,680
and called me a two-bit
grocery clerk from Whittier.

1042
01:12:40,900 --> 01:12:43,280
That's the last time I ever saw him.

1043
01:12:47,660 --> 01:12:52,870
See, when I saw Bobby
lying there on the floor,

1044
01:12:52,960 --> 01:12:56,710
arms stretched out like that,
his eyes staring...

1045
01:12:59,500 --> 01:13:02,090
...I knew then I'd be president.

1046
01:13:03,260 --> 01:13:06,760
His death paved the way, didn't it?

1047
01:13:06,840 --> 01:13:09,930
Yeah. Vietnam, the Kennedys

1048
01:13:10,010 --> 01:13:13,310
cleared a path
through the wilderness just for me.

1049
01:13:15,390 --> 01:13:17,360
Over the bodies.

1050
01:13:19,980 --> 01:13:21,690
Four bodies.

1051
01:13:28,870 --> 01:13:30,410
You mean two.

1052
01:13:31,740 --> 01:13:33,750
Two bodies.

1053
01:13:35,120 --> 01:13:38,170
Four.

1054
01:13:50,140 --> 01:13:52,970
How many did you have?

1055
01:13:53,060 --> 01:13:55,230
Hundreds of thousands?

1056
01:13:59,440 --> 01:14:02,400
Where would we be without death, huh?

1057
01:14:04,570 --> 01:14:06,150
Abe?

1058
01:14:11,910 --> 01:14:13,830
Who's helping us?

1059
01:14:15,040 --> 01:14:18,250
Is it God, or is it...

1060
01:14:19,830 --> 01:14:21,460
...death?

1061
01:15:15,010 --> 01:15:16,430
Harold.

1062
01:15:17,810 --> 01:15:19,810
Harold, why don't you sit down, huh?

1063
01:15:22,690 --> 01:15:24,070
Here.

1064
01:15:28,320 --> 01:15:29,990
That was a whopper.

1065
01:15:36,080 --> 01:15:38,200
You'll be able to do it now.

1066
01:15:39,580 --> 01:15:42,420
- What?
- Go to law school.

1067
01:15:42,500 --> 01:15:45,670
- Mom and Dad'll be able to afford it.
- Harold.

1068
01:15:46,750 --> 01:15:49,170
Mama expects great things from you.

1069
01:15:50,300 --> 01:15:53,180
Can I... Can I get you anything?

1070
01:15:56,310 --> 01:15:57,890
Relax, Dick.

1071
01:15:59,100 --> 01:16:01,230
It's just me, all right?

1072
01:16:07,150 --> 01:16:09,530
The desert's so beautiful, isn't it?

1073
01:16:15,990 --> 01:16:17,870
I want to go home, Dick.

1074
01:16:19,040 --> 01:16:20,960
Time to go home.

1075
01:16:22,370 --> 01:16:26,880
You... You're not gonna quit
on me now, are you, Harold?

1076
01:17:13,720 --> 01:17:15,380
Richard.

1077
01:17:17,720 --> 01:17:21,060
- I can't.
- You must.

1078
01:17:22,270 --> 01:17:26,900
This law school,
it's a gift from thy brother.

1079
01:17:26,980 --> 01:17:30,230
He had to die for me to get it?

1080
01:17:34,110 --> 01:17:36,860
Something has to come of this.

1081
01:17:38,410 --> 01:17:41,490
It's meant to make us stronger.

1082
01:17:41,580 --> 01:17:45,370
Thee art stronger than Harold,
stronger than Arthur.

1083
01:17:45,460 --> 01:17:51,300
- God has chosen thee to survive.
- What about happiness, Mother?

1084
01:17:53,590 --> 01:17:57,550
Thee will find thy peace
at the center, Richard.

1085
01:17:57,640 --> 01:18:02,430
Strength in this life,
happiness in the next.

1086
01:18:50,520 --> 01:18:52,980
Now tell me you didn't want this, Buddy.

1087
01:19:01,700 --> 01:19:03,080
Hey!

1088
01:19:22,510 --> 01:19:25,970
When the strongest nation
in the world can be tied down

1089
01:19:26,060 --> 01:19:30,350
for four years in a war in Vietnam
with no end in sight,

1090
01:19:30,440 --> 01:19:34,770
when the richest nation in the world
can't manage its own economy,

1091
01:19:34,860 --> 01:19:38,320
when the nation with the greatest
tradition of the rule of law

1092
01:19:38,400 --> 01:19:41,660
is plagued by unprecedented lawlessness,

1093
01:19:41,740 --> 01:19:45,870
when a nation that has been known for
a century for equality of opportunity

1094
01:19:45,950 --> 01:19:49,460
is torn by unprecedented
racial violence,

1095
01:19:49,540 --> 01:19:53,080
when the president of the United States
cannot travel abroad

1096
01:19:53,170 --> 01:19:57,630
or to any major city at home without
fear of a hostile demonstration,

1097
01:19:57,710 --> 01:20:02,800
then it is time for new leadership
for the United States of America.

1098
01:20:05,600 --> 01:20:09,680
As we look at America, we see cities
enveloped in smoke and flame,

1099
01:20:09,770 --> 01:20:12,310
millions of Americans
crying out in anguish,

1100
01:20:12,390 --> 01:20:17,820
"Did we come all the way for this?
Did American boys die in Normandy

1101
01:20:17,900 --> 01:20:20,610
and Valley Forge for this?"

1102
01:20:20,690 --> 01:20:24,160
I pledge to you
that the current wave of violence

1103
01:20:24,240 --> 01:20:26,330
will not be the wave of the future.

1104
01:20:28,950 --> 01:20:32,750
Now let us begin
by committing ourselves to the truth,

1105
01:20:32,830 --> 01:20:36,880
to find the truth, to speak the truth
and to live the truth.

1106
01:20:36,960 --> 01:20:40,420
A new voice is being heard
across America today.

1107
01:20:40,510 --> 01:20:43,380
It is not the voice
of the protesters or the shouters.

1108
01:20:43,470 --> 01:20:47,640
It is the quiet voice of the majority
of Americans who've been forgotten,

1109
01:20:47,720 --> 01:20:51,060
the non-shouters,
the, uh, non-demonstrators.

1110
01:20:51,140 --> 01:20:56,110
They're the good people. They work hard
and they save and they pay their taxes.

1111
01:20:56,190 --> 01:20:58,610
Now, who are they?
Let me tell you who they are.

1112
01:20:58,690 --> 01:21:00,900
They're in this audience
by the thousands.

1113
01:21:00,990 --> 01:21:03,530
They're the white Americans
and black Americans,

1114
01:21:03,610 --> 01:21:06,240
Mexican Americans
and Italian Americans.

1115
01:21:06,320 --> 01:21:08,620
They're the great silent majority,

1116
01:21:08,700 --> 01:21:12,120
and they have become angry, finally.
Angry, not with hate,

1117
01:21:12,200 --> 01:21:14,870
but angry, my friends,
because they love America

1118
01:21:14,960 --> 01:21:19,170
and they don't like what's happened
to America these last four years.

1119
01:21:19,250 --> 01:21:24,550
Let us understand North Vietnam cannot
defeat or humiliate the United States.

1120
01:21:24,630 --> 01:21:26,720
Only Americans can do that!

1121
01:21:30,100 --> 01:21:31,930
I say to you tonight...

1122
01:21:32,020 --> 01:21:36,020
I say to you tonight we must have
a new feeling of responsibility,

1123
01:21:36,100 --> 01:21:40,400
of self-discipline. We must look
to renew state and local government.

1124
01:21:40,480 --> 01:21:45,530
We must have a complete reform
of a big, bloated federal government.

1125
01:21:45,610 --> 01:21:47,740
Those of us in public service know

1126
01:21:47,820 --> 01:21:50,740
we can have full prosperity
in peacetime.

1127
01:21:50,830 --> 01:21:52,950
Yes, we can cut the defense budget.

1128
01:21:53,040 --> 01:21:55,960
We can reduce, uh,
conventional forces in Europe.

1129
01:21:56,040 --> 01:21:58,130
We can restore the natural environment.

1130
01:21:58,210 --> 01:22:01,380
We can improve health care,
make it more available to all people.

1131
01:22:01,460 --> 01:22:04,970
And yes, we can have a complete reform
of this government.

1132
01:22:05,050 --> 01:22:08,390
We can have a new American revolution!

1133
01:22:21,400 --> 01:22:24,940
The whole world is watching!
The whole world is watching!

1134
01:22:34,040 --> 01:22:36,000
It'd be a disaster.

1135
01:22:36,080 --> 01:22:39,290
There's a lot of sympathy
out there for Cambodia.

1136
01:22:39,380 --> 01:22:42,460
Tiny, little, neutral Buddhist country.

1137
01:22:42,540 --> 01:22:45,760
They'll be rioting in the streets,
on your front lawn!

1138
01:22:45,840 --> 01:22:50,340
Building the Cambodian army up? That
would be harder than a Vietnamese Army.

1139
01:22:50,430 --> 01:22:55,430
They have no tradition. Mr. President,
the government there will collapse.

1140
01:22:55,520 --> 01:22:58,770
- So you're saying do nothing.
- No, sir, continue the bombing.

1141
01:22:58,850 --> 01:23:01,690
The same old horseshit.
Well, that's not good enough.

1142
01:23:01,770 --> 01:23:04,320
I'm sick of being pushed around
by the Vietnamese

1143
01:23:04,400 --> 01:23:08,360
like we're some, uh,
you know, pitiful giant.

1144
01:23:08,450 --> 01:23:11,320
They're using our POWs
to humiliate us.

1145
01:23:11,410 --> 01:23:14,240
What we need now
is a bold move into Cambodia

1146
01:23:14,330 --> 01:23:17,660
and go right after their
VC base camps

1147
01:23:17,750 --> 01:23:21,830
and, uh... make 'em scream,
hit 'em in the ass.

1148
01:23:21,920 --> 01:23:25,210
- What do you think, Henry?
- Well, as you know,

1149
01:23:25,300 --> 01:23:28,720
most of my staff have weighed in
against this incursion.

1150
01:23:28,800 --> 01:23:33,720
They believe it will fail to achieve
anything fundamental militarily

1151
01:23:33,800 --> 01:23:37,140
and will result
in crushing criticism domestically.

1152
01:23:37,220 --> 01:23:41,060
I didn't ask what your staff thinks.
What do you think, Henry?

1153
01:23:41,150 --> 01:23:43,810
What I think is they're cowards.

1154
01:23:43,900 --> 01:23:47,440
Their opposition
represents the cowardice

1155
01:23:47,530 --> 01:23:51,950
of the eastern establishment.
They don't realize, as you do, sir,

1156
01:23:52,030 --> 01:23:54,580
that the Communists
only respect strength

1157
01:23:54,660 --> 01:23:57,040
and they will only negotiate
in good faith

1158
01:23:57,120 --> 01:23:59,910
if they fear the mad man, Richard Nixon.

1159
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:03,710
Exactly!
Unpredictability is our best asset.

1160
01:24:03,790 --> 01:24:07,500
We gotta take the war to 'em, hit 'em
where it hurts, right in the nuts.

1161
01:24:07,590 --> 01:24:11,880
- More assassinations. Right, Al?
- That's what they're doing.

1162
01:24:11,970 --> 01:24:15,680
See, your people in the State
Department, Bill, they don't understand.

1163
01:24:15,760 --> 01:24:18,600
- Mr. President...
- Electrify people with bold moves.

1164
01:24:18,680 --> 01:24:23,190
Bold moves make history.
Like, uh... Teddy Roosevelt, TR,

1165
01:24:23,270 --> 01:24:27,230
rushing up San Juan Hill.
Small event, but dramatic.

1166
01:24:27,320 --> 01:24:30,360
- People took notice.
- They'll take notice, all right.

1167
01:24:30,440 --> 01:24:35,450
If we sneak out of this war,
another will start a mile down the road.

1168
01:24:35,530 --> 01:24:39,290
We bite the bullet here in Cambodia.
There.

1169
01:24:40,120 --> 01:24:42,160
We bomb the hell out of these people.

1170
01:24:46,670 --> 01:24:49,550
Tonight, American
and South Vietnamese units

1171
01:24:49,630 --> 01:24:51,380
will attack the headquarters

1172
01:24:51,470 --> 01:24:55,550
for the entire Communist military
operation in South Vietnam.

1173
01:24:55,640 --> 01:24:58,810
This is not an invasion of Cambodia.

1174
01:24:58,890 --> 01:25:03,980
We take this action not for the purpose
of expanding the war into Cambodia,

1175
01:25:04,060 --> 01:25:07,400
but for the purpose
of ending the war in Vietnam.

1176
01:25:12,280 --> 01:25:13,860
<i>All across the nation,</i>

1177
01:25:13,950 --> 01:25:16,660
<i>major student protests
against the U.S. invasion</i>

1178
01:25:16,740 --> 01:25:19,490
<i>of Cambodia rocked college campuses.</i>

1179
01:25:19,580 --> 01:25:23,250
<i>At Jackson State, two Negro students
were killed and ten were wounded.</i>

1180
01:25:23,330 --> 01:25:26,790
<i>- ...unanimously and united behind...
- In the streets of New York,</i>

1181
01:25:26,880 --> 01:25:29,420
<i>protesters were attacked
by construction workers</i>

1182
01:25:29,500 --> 01:25:32,710
<i>supporting President Nixon's policies.</i>

1183
01:25:33,970 --> 01:25:37,340
<i>In Washington, protesters
have barricaded the White House</i>

1184
01:25:37,430 --> 01:25:39,470
<i>and are camping out
at the Lincoln Memorial.</i>

1185
01:25:51,070 --> 01:25:55,110
See, when I think of those kids
out there in Vietnam doing their duty,

1186
01:25:55,200 --> 01:25:58,280
uh, I bet they were scared.
I was when I was there.

1187
01:25:58,740 --> 01:26:00,240
But when it comes down to it,

1188
01:26:00,330 --> 01:26:04,450
you really have to look up to these men
because they're the greatest.

1189
01:26:09,460 --> 01:26:11,300
I mean, you see these bums, you know,

1190
01:26:11,380 --> 01:26:14,880
blowing up the campuses,
burning books and so forth.

1191
01:26:14,970 --> 01:26:18,050
And they call themselves
"flower children."

1192
01:26:18,140 --> 01:26:21,890
I call them spoiled rotten.
And I tell you what would cure them.

1193
01:26:21,970 --> 01:26:26,350
A good, old-fashioned trip to my Ohio
father's woodshed. Right, Julie?

1194
01:26:26,440 --> 01:26:29,190
- Right, Dad.
- That's what these bums need.

1195
01:26:29,270 --> 01:26:32,400
- Well, thanks and congratulations.
- Thank you, sir.

1196
01:26:32,480 --> 01:26:35,490
Yeah. OK. Thanks, everybody. Bye.

1197
01:26:36,570 --> 01:26:38,780
The whole world is watching.

1198
01:26:56,720 --> 01:26:57,090
<i>Less than 24 hours after
President Nixon called them bums,</i>

1199
01:26:57,090 --> 01:27:00,760
<i>Less than 24 hours after
President Nixon called them bums,</i>

1200
01:27:00,840 --> 01:27:04,770
<i>four students were shot dead
at Kent State University in Ohio.</i>

1201
01:27:04,850 --> 01:27:07,770
<i>Enraged student groups are calling</i>

1202
01:27:07,850 --> 01:27:10,270
<i>for a general strike
tomorrow to shut down...</i>

1203
01:27:10,350 --> 01:27:14,570
I tell you, the soldiers were provoked.
Now, stop this pussyfooting around.

1204
01:27:14,650 --> 01:27:16,190
Jesus Christ, dead kids.

1205
01:27:16,280 --> 01:27:19,280
How the hell did we give the Democrats
a weapon like this?

1206
01:27:19,360 --> 01:27:22,530
Well, one way or the other,
Kent State is not good.

1207
01:27:22,620 --> 01:27:25,740
- We have to get out in front of this.
- Follow the money.

1208
01:27:25,830 --> 01:27:29,290
- Sir?
- These kids are manipulated

1209
01:27:29,370 --> 01:27:32,330
by the Communists,
like Chambers and Hiss.

1210
01:27:32,420 --> 01:27:33,920
What's the matter with you?

1211
01:27:34,000 --> 01:27:38,130
- This isn't '48. They'll never buy it.
- How do you know that, John?

1212
01:27:38,220 --> 01:27:40,130
What's Hoover found,
for God's sake?

1213
01:27:40,220 --> 01:27:44,510
He called the other day, sir.
He asked for President Harding.

1214
01:27:45,220 --> 01:27:48,810
- We can have a national prayer day.
- Never complain, never explain.

1215
01:27:48,890 --> 01:27:52,850
Come on, these
are not fraternity pranks, John.

1216
01:27:52,940 --> 01:27:55,110
No, this is anarchy.
It's a revolution.

1217
01:27:55,190 --> 01:27:58,190
- I wouldn't go that far, sir.
- Why not?

1218
01:27:59,400 --> 01:28:03,700
Well, is it worth it, sir? I mean,
is the war worth a one-term presidency?

1219
01:28:03,780 --> 01:28:06,160
Right now I think
that's what we're looking at.

1220
01:28:06,240 --> 01:28:09,450
I will not go down as the first
American president to lose a war.

1221
01:28:09,540 --> 01:28:12,500
Going to Cambodia, bombing Hanoi,
bombing Laos buys us time

1222
01:28:12,580 --> 01:28:15,420
so we can get out and give
the South Vietnamese a chance.

1223
01:28:15,500 --> 01:28:19,340
- Exactly, sir.
- If we keep our heads, we'll win this.

1224
01:28:19,420 --> 01:28:21,930
- What, win Vietnam, sir?
- No, no.

1225
01:28:22,880 --> 01:28:27,180
No, but we can drive a stake through
the heart of the Communist alliance.

1226
01:28:27,260 --> 01:28:30,480
Henry's getting strong signals
from the Chinese.

1227
01:28:30,560 --> 01:28:33,150
They fear the Vietnamese
more than the Russians

1228
01:28:33,230 --> 01:28:36,150
and they're worried
about a united Vietnam.

1229
01:28:36,230 --> 01:28:39,400
Now, if we stick it out,
we'll end up negotiating separately

1230
01:28:39,480 --> 01:28:42,200
with both the Chinese and the Soviets.

1231
01:28:42,280 --> 01:28:45,530
And we'll get better deals
than we ever dreamed of from both.

1232
01:28:45,620 --> 01:28:51,120
- That is triangular diplomacy.
- Exactly, Mr. President.

1233
01:28:51,200 --> 01:28:54,210
That's what geopolitics is about.

1234
01:28:54,290 --> 01:28:57,880
The linking of the whole world
for self-interest.

1235
01:28:57,960 --> 01:29:00,800
You tell me, Ron,
how the hell I can explain that on TV

1236
01:29:00,880 --> 01:29:04,130
to a bunch of simpleminded reporters
and, uh, weeping mothers.

1237
01:29:04,220 --> 01:29:06,010
But what am I telling the press

1238
01:29:06,090 --> 01:29:08,640
- about Kent State?
- Tell 'em what the hell you like.

1239
01:29:08,720 --> 01:29:11,850
- They don't understand anyway.
- Excuse me, sir.

1240
01:29:13,140 --> 01:29:16,060
Are you saying you're
gonna recognize Red China?

1241
01:29:16,150 --> 01:29:18,860
That would cost us
our strongest support.

1242
01:29:18,940 --> 01:29:21,740
No, I can do this because
I spent my whole career

1243
01:29:21,820 --> 01:29:25,570
- building anti-Communist credentials.
- If Kennedy or Johnson tried it,

1244
01:29:25,660 --> 01:29:28,120
they'd have crucified them,
and rightfully so.

1245
01:29:28,200 --> 01:29:32,290
Damned risky, Mr. President.
Why don't we wait until the second term?

1246
01:29:32,370 --> 01:29:35,580
- This will get us a second term.
- This will get me a second term.

1247
01:29:35,670 --> 01:29:39,460
Damn it, without risk, there's
no heroism, there's no history.

1248
01:29:39,540 --> 01:29:42,260
Nixon was born to do this.
Give history a nudge.

1249
01:29:42,340 --> 01:29:43,880
- Come on!
- Hear, hear.

1250
01:29:43,970 --> 01:29:48,180
If Cambodia doesn't work,
we'll bomb Hanoi if we have to.

1251
01:29:48,260 --> 01:29:51,810
That's right.
And if necessary, I'll drop the big one.

1252
01:29:55,560 --> 01:29:58,230
We have to entertain the possibility.

1253
01:30:03,690 --> 01:30:06,400
Goddamn it! Who cooked this damn steak?

1254
01:30:06,490 --> 01:30:09,320
Manolo, there's blood all over my plate.
Take it away.

1255
01:30:09,410 --> 01:30:11,030
I'm sorry, sir.

1256
01:30:23,920 --> 01:30:25,590
You all right?

1257
01:30:26,720 --> 01:30:28,220
Yeah.

1258
01:30:29,590 --> 01:30:33,600
My brother, Harold,
was the same age as those kids, John.

1259
01:30:33,680 --> 01:30:38,150
- Tuberculosis got him.
- It wasn't your fault.

1260
01:30:38,230 --> 01:30:42,150
The soldiers were kids too.
They just panicked.

1261
01:30:42,230 --> 01:30:43,400
Yeah.

1262
01:30:44,820 --> 01:30:48,160
They were throwing rocks,
John, just rocks.

1263
01:30:51,070 --> 01:30:53,080
They don't think I feel,

1264
01:30:53,160 --> 01:30:56,160
but I feel too much sometimes.

1265
01:30:57,160 --> 01:31:01,210
I just can't let a whole policy
be dominated by our sentimentality.

1266
01:31:01,290 --> 01:31:05,170
You're doing the right thing.
Don't let 'em shake you.

1267
01:31:07,260 --> 01:31:10,430
You know, it broke my heart
when Harold died.

1268
01:31:10,510 --> 01:31:13,310
That was a long time ago.

1269
01:31:14,600 --> 01:31:16,310
Yeah.

1270
01:31:16,390 --> 01:31:19,520
I think that's when it starts,
when you're a kid.

1271
01:31:19,600 --> 01:31:23,440
The laughs and snubs
and slights you get

1272
01:31:23,520 --> 01:31:26,860
because you're poor or Irish

1273
01:31:26,940 --> 01:31:30,530
or Jewish or just ugly.

1274
01:31:31,740 --> 01:31:35,120
Get off that. That leads nowhere.

1275
01:31:36,080 --> 01:31:40,330
But you should offer condolences
to the families of those kids.

1276
01:31:40,420 --> 01:31:41,790
Sure.

1277
01:31:43,080 --> 01:31:46,880
I'd like to.
I'd like to offer my condolences.

1278
01:31:49,800 --> 01:31:51,760
But Nixon can't.

1279
01:32:06,480 --> 01:32:09,240
<i>Enraged student groups
across the country</i>

1280
01:32:09,320 --> 01:32:11,400
<i>are calling for
a general strike tomorrow</i>

1281
01:32:11,490 --> 01:32:15,870
<i>to shut down the entire university
system until the Vietnam War is ended.</i>

1282
01:32:15,950 --> 01:32:18,540
Oh, this is nothing
compared to Venezuela.

1283
01:32:18,620 --> 01:32:22,500
When I was vice president, Ike sent me
down there like a blocking tackle.

1284
01:32:22,580 --> 01:32:25,500
They threw rocks, broke out windows.

1285
01:32:25,590 --> 01:32:28,670
<i>Almost overturned the car.
Read Six Crises, Bob.</i>

1286
01:32:28,760 --> 01:32:31,130
- I did, sir.
- Pat was brave.

1287
01:32:35,640 --> 01:32:39,430
Jesus, they're serious.
Why are we stopping? Come on, move it!

1288
01:32:44,810 --> 01:32:47,940
- Jesus!
- Get that little punk!

1289
01:32:48,020 --> 01:32:49,900
Tackle! Go on, get him!

1290
01:32:49,990 --> 01:32:51,110
Yeah!

1291
01:32:53,740 --> 01:32:56,870
Yeah. Reminds me
of my days at Whittier.

1292
01:32:56,950 --> 01:32:59,620
- These kids are useless.
- Probably flunking.

1293
01:32:59,700 --> 01:33:02,410
Nothing to do except come here
and chase girls.

1294
01:33:03,210 --> 01:33:06,960
Their parents' fault.
They're poisoning the upper class, Bob.

1295
01:33:07,040 --> 01:33:10,630
- Too soft, too many cars, color TVs.
- Don't forget the South, the West.

1296
01:33:10,710 --> 01:33:13,430
Good football colleges.
More with than against you.

1297
01:33:13,510 --> 01:33:17,050
Let's not forget they're just kids.
They don't vote.

1298
01:33:17,140 --> 01:33:19,850
This is the fall of the Roman Empire.
Are you blind?

1299
01:33:19,930 --> 01:33:22,310
We're putting the fig leaves
on the statues.

1300
01:33:33,190 --> 01:33:35,070
Mr. President.

1301
01:33:35,160 --> 01:33:37,700
- Bob.
- I don't know what to say, sir.

1302
01:33:37,780 --> 01:33:41,080
Soon as we learned from the Secret
Service that you were en route,

1303
01:33:41,160 --> 01:33:43,580
the director was notified.
He should be here.

1304
01:33:43,660 --> 01:33:47,960
- So where the hell is he?
- Rushing back from his tennis game.

1305
01:33:49,090 --> 01:33:50,920
- So let's go.
- Told me to take you

1306
01:33:51,000 --> 01:33:53,210
- to his conference room.
- No, his office.

1307
01:33:53,300 --> 01:33:56,590
I want a private conversation with him.
I don't wanna be bugged.

1308
01:33:56,680 --> 01:33:58,470
- Then his office will be fine.
- OK.

1309
01:34:07,350 --> 01:34:08,690
All right.

1310
01:34:10,610 --> 01:34:14,280
- How's the job going, Bob?
- Frankly, it stinks, sir.

1311
01:34:14,360 --> 01:34:16,280
I have no access.

1312
01:34:17,570 --> 01:34:21,240
- We'll see to that.
- He's nervous, sir.

1313
01:34:21,330 --> 01:34:24,160
He's heard you're looking
for a new director.

1314
01:34:24,250 --> 01:34:27,710
- Certainly isn't acting like it.
- That's Helms.

1315
01:34:27,790 --> 01:34:32,710
He's the epitome of sang-froid.
A world-class poker player.

1316
01:34:32,800 --> 01:34:35,510
Yeah? Well, I own the fucking casino.

1317
01:34:42,260 --> 01:34:46,430
I'm honored, Dick,
that you've come all the way out here

1318
01:34:46,520 --> 01:34:49,150
to Virginia to visit us at last.

1319
01:34:51,440 --> 01:34:54,530
- My friends call me Mr. President.
- Then so shall I.

1320
01:34:54,610 --> 01:34:57,990
- Mr. Helms.
- Arrange for some coffee,

1321
01:34:58,070 --> 01:34:59,910
will you, General Cushman?

1322
01:35:02,330 --> 01:35:03,870
Gentleman, please.

1323
01:35:10,500 --> 01:35:14,840
Bob Cushman is a lieutenant general
in the Marine Corps,

1324
01:35:14,920 --> 01:35:18,590
deputy director of the CIA.

1325
01:35:18,680 --> 01:35:23,220
- This is what you use him for?
- I didn't choose him as my deputy.

1326
01:35:23,300 --> 01:35:28,020
- You did.
- You live pretty well out here.

1327
01:35:28,100 --> 01:35:31,600
I understand why you keep
your budgets classified.

1328
01:35:32,900 --> 01:35:35,780
I suppose you're unhappy...

1329
01:35:37,240 --> 01:35:41,700
...because I haven't implemented
your domestic intelligence plan.

1330
01:35:41,780 --> 01:35:43,370
Yeah, you're correct.

1331
01:35:43,450 --> 01:35:46,950
I'm concerned these students
are being funded by foreign interests

1332
01:35:47,040 --> 01:35:50,960
whether they know it or not.
The FBI's useless in this area.

1333
01:35:51,040 --> 01:35:53,460
I want your full attention
on this matter.

1334
01:35:53,540 --> 01:35:56,250
We've tried, but so far
we've come up with nothing.

1335
01:35:56,340 --> 01:35:59,420
Then find something!
I want these leaks stopped.

1336
01:35:59,510 --> 01:36:03,300
Jack Anderson, The New York Times,
the State Department.

1337
01:36:03,390 --> 01:36:06,390
- I wanna know who's talking.
- I'm sure you realize

1338
01:36:06,470 --> 01:36:08,730
that this is a tricky area,

1339
01:36:08,810 --> 01:36:12,440
given our charter and
the Congressional oversight committee.

1340
01:36:12,520 --> 01:36:16,320
Screw congressional oversight.
I know damn well, going back to the '50s

1341
01:36:16,400 --> 01:36:20,200
this agency reports what it wants
and buries what it wants.

1342
01:36:20,280 --> 01:36:25,280
- Pay close attention to this.
- Is something else bothering you?

1343
01:36:25,370 --> 01:36:26,950
Yes.

1344
01:36:27,040 --> 01:36:29,660
It involves some old
and forgotten papers...

1345
01:36:30,870 --> 01:36:33,080
...things I signed as vice president.

1346
01:36:33,170 --> 01:36:38,300
I want the original in my office
and I don't want copies anywhere else.

1347
01:36:39,510 --> 01:36:42,180
You're referring, I believe,

1348
01:36:42,260 --> 01:36:45,600
to chairing
the special operations group

1349
01:36:45,680 --> 01:36:48,520
- as vice president.
- Yeah.

1350
01:36:49,850 --> 01:36:52,640
As you know, that was unique.

1351
01:36:54,400 --> 01:36:59,150
Not an operation so much
as an organic phenomenon.

1352
01:36:59,230 --> 01:37:03,570
It grew, it changed shape,

1353
01:37:03,660 --> 01:37:07,370
it developed appetites.

1354
01:37:08,660 --> 01:37:13,670
It's not unusual in such cases
that things aren't committed to paper.

1355
01:37:14,670 --> 01:37:16,580
That could be very embarrassing.

1356
01:37:17,790 --> 01:37:22,340
I, for one, saw to it that my name was
never connected with these operations.

1357
01:37:23,300 --> 01:37:24,380
Diem.

1358
01:37:28,430 --> 01:37:30,010
Trujillo.

1359
01:37:30,100 --> 01:37:31,390
Lumumba.

1360
01:37:31,470 --> 01:37:32,680
Guatemala.

1361
01:37:35,060 --> 01:37:37,190
Iran.

1362
01:37:37,730 --> 01:37:38,860
Cuba.

1363
01:37:47,200 --> 01:37:51,450
It's a shame you didn't
take similar precautions, Dick.

1364
01:37:57,000 --> 01:38:00,960
I'm interested in those documents
that put your people together

1365
01:38:01,050 --> 01:38:03,510
with the gangster elements.

1366
01:38:04,840 --> 01:38:07,890
- All the documents.
- President Kennedy threatened

1367
01:38:07,970 --> 01:38:11,220
to smash the CIA into 1,000 pieces.

1368
01:38:11,310 --> 01:38:13,350
You could do the same.

1369
01:38:15,480 --> 01:38:17,600
I'm not Jack Kennedy. Uh...

1370
01:38:17,690 --> 01:38:22,480
- Your agency is secure.
- Not if I give you all the cards.

1371
01:38:28,360 --> 01:38:32,700
I promised the American people
peace with honor in Southeast Asia.

1372
01:38:34,160 --> 01:38:38,290
That may take time.
Two, maybe three years.

1373
01:38:38,370 --> 01:38:42,000
But, in the meantime,
your agency will continue

1374
01:38:42,090 --> 01:38:44,550
at current levels of funding.

1375
01:38:46,050 --> 01:38:49,140
Current levels may not be sufficient.

1376
01:38:49,220 --> 01:38:54,140
Well, the president will support
a reasonable request for an increase.

1377
01:38:54,220 --> 01:38:55,930
And me?

1378
01:38:57,440 --> 01:39:00,860
Of course,
you will continue as DCI, Dick.

1379
01:39:01,900 --> 01:39:03,860
You're doing a magnificent job.

1380
01:39:06,190 --> 01:39:08,780
Of course, I accept. I'm flattered.

1381
01:39:10,110 --> 01:39:15,240
And I want you to know that
I serve only one president at a time.

1382
01:39:15,330 --> 01:39:20,420
Yes. And you'll give
General Cushman full access.

1383
01:39:24,250 --> 01:39:26,920
It could take a little time.

1384
01:39:27,010 --> 01:39:29,720
But I'll order a search
for your papers.

1385
01:39:29,800 --> 01:39:32,640
- Good.
- It does raise...

1386
01:39:32,720 --> 01:39:35,930
- ...a troubling issue.
- What?

1387
01:39:36,020 --> 01:39:38,350
Castro.

1388
01:39:39,600 --> 01:39:43,400
- Yes?
- We have recent intelligence

1389
01:39:43,480 --> 01:39:46,480
that a Soviet nuclear submarine

1390
01:39:46,570 --> 01:39:51,990
- has docked at Cienfuegos.
- We'll launch a formal protest.

1391
01:39:52,070 --> 01:39:56,290
I don't think we can treat this
as a formality.

1392
01:39:57,830 --> 01:40:02,880
Mr. Kennedy gave the Russians a verbal
promise that he would not invade Cuba.

1393
01:40:02,960 --> 01:40:07,000
But you authorized Dr. Kissinger
to put this in writing?

1394
01:40:10,050 --> 01:40:14,220
- Are you tapping Kissinger?
- My job, unpleasant at times,

1395
01:40:14,300 --> 01:40:16,640
is to know what others
don't want me to know.

1396
01:40:16,720 --> 01:40:20,180
Not if you have spies
in the White House.

1397
01:40:20,270 --> 01:40:23,400
It is not my practice
to spy on the president.

1398
01:40:23,480 --> 01:40:27,190
Dr. Kissinger manages to convey his
innermost secrets to the world

1399
01:40:27,280 --> 01:40:29,110
without my help.

1400
01:40:30,400 --> 01:40:32,240
Dick...

1401
01:40:32,320 --> 01:40:36,030
We've lived with communism in Cuba
for ten years.

1402
01:40:36,120 --> 01:40:39,750
But it's never been the policy
of this government to accept that.

1403
01:40:39,830 --> 01:40:44,080
- And it's certainly not CIA policy.
- CIA policy?

1404
01:40:44,170 --> 01:40:48,380
The CIA has no policy
except what I dictate to you.

1405
01:40:50,970 --> 01:40:55,550
I tried to, uh, adjust to the world
as it is today,

1406
01:40:55,640 --> 01:40:59,220
not as you or I wanted it
to be ten years ago.

1407
01:40:59,310 --> 01:41:03,020
Is that why you and Kissinger
are negotiating with the Chinese?

1408
01:41:04,350 --> 01:41:08,480
This is a very dangerous direction,
Mr. President.

1409
01:41:08,570 --> 01:41:12,740
Terrible consequences can result
from such enormous errors of judgment.

1410
01:41:14,740 --> 01:41:18,620
If we were able to separate
China from Russia once and for all,

1411
01:41:18,700 --> 01:41:21,250
we can, we could create
a balance of power

1412
01:41:21,330 --> 01:41:23,960
that would secure peace
into the next century.

1413
01:41:24,040 --> 01:41:27,460
And offer Cuba to the Russians
as a consolation prize?

1414
01:41:29,590 --> 01:41:35,300
- Cuba would be a small price to pay.
- So President Kennedy thought.

1415
01:41:39,720 --> 01:41:44,230
I never thought Kennedy
was ready for the presidency.

1416
01:41:48,690 --> 01:41:50,650
Well, now...

1417
01:41:50,730 --> 01:41:53,400
...I would never, uh...

1418
01:41:53,490 --> 01:41:56,200
...never consider...

1419
01:41:57,740 --> 01:41:59,830
His death was awful.

1420
01:42:00,950 --> 01:42:03,410
It was an awful thing
for this country.

1421
01:42:05,710 --> 01:42:07,080
Yeah.

1422
01:42:09,710 --> 01:42:12,340
Do you ever think of death, Dick?

1423
01:42:13,760 --> 01:42:17,640
Flowers are a continual reminder
of our mortality.

1424
01:42:18,640 --> 01:42:21,760
- Do you appreciate flowers?
- No.

1425
01:42:23,390 --> 01:42:26,640
No, they make me sick
and they smell like death.

1426
01:42:28,770 --> 01:42:31,110
I had two brothers die young.

1427
01:42:32,940 --> 01:42:34,900
Let me tell you,

1428
01:42:34,990 --> 01:42:37,530
there are worse things than death.

1429
01:42:37,610 --> 01:42:39,070
Yes.

1430
01:42:42,080 --> 01:42:44,830
There's such a thing as evil.

1431
01:42:47,290 --> 01:42:51,710
You must be familiar
with my favorite poem by Yeats,

1432
01:42:51,790 --> 01:42:53,800
<i>The Second Coming.</i>

1433
01:42:56,470 --> 01:42:58,890
Black Irish, very moving.

1434
01:43:01,470 --> 01:43:06,230
Turning and turning
in the widening gyre

1435
01:43:06,310 --> 01:43:10,400
The falcon cannot hear the falconer

1436
01:43:10,480 --> 01:43:13,480
Things fall apart

1437
01:43:13,570 --> 01:43:17,360
The center cannot hold

1438
01:43:17,450 --> 01:43:21,820
Mere anarchy is loosed upon the world

1439
01:43:21,910 --> 01:43:26,950
And everywhere, the ceremony
of innocence is lost

1440
01:43:27,040 --> 01:43:31,290
The best lack all conviction

1441
01:43:31,380 --> 01:43:37,340
And the worst are full
of passionate intensity

1442
01:43:39,840 --> 01:43:42,680
But it ends so beautifully ominous.

1443
01:43:44,390 --> 01:43:47,270
What rough beast

1444
01:43:47,350 --> 01:43:51,310
Its hour come round at last

1445
01:43:51,400 --> 01:43:56,400
Slouches toward Bethlehem
to be born?

1446
01:43:58,740 --> 01:44:00,280
Yes.

1447
01:44:01,530 --> 01:44:05,160
This country stands at such a juncture.

1448
01:44:10,620 --> 01:44:12,210
Manolo?

1449
01:44:16,210 --> 01:44:17,630
Mano?

1450
01:44:17,710 --> 01:44:20,420
- Mr. President.
- Yeah.

1451
01:44:20,510 --> 01:44:23,970
I'm sorry. I was asleep.

1452
01:44:25,220 --> 01:44:26,970
What can I get you?

1453
01:44:28,390 --> 01:44:31,060
- Well, you know.
- Of course.

1454
01:44:45,450 --> 01:44:48,330
Do you miss Cuba, Manolo?

1455
01:44:49,450 --> 01:44:51,410
Yes, Mr. President.

1456
01:44:56,590 --> 01:45:01,010
We let you down, didn't we?
Your people.

1457
01:45:01,090 --> 01:45:04,140
That was Mr. Kennedy, sir.

1458
01:45:10,430 --> 01:45:13,350
You don't think he was a hero, do you?

1459
01:45:15,440 --> 01:45:18,270
He was a politician.

1460
01:45:28,030 --> 01:45:30,240
Did you cry when he died?

1461
01:45:34,500 --> 01:45:36,000
Yes, sir.

1462
01:45:37,590 --> 01:45:38,960
Why?

1463
01:45:40,380 --> 01:45:42,720
I don't know.

1464
01:45:44,050 --> 01:45:47,640
He made me...

1465
01:45:47,720 --> 01:45:50,310
...see the stars.

1466
01:45:57,190 --> 01:45:59,480
How did he do that?

1467
01:46:01,820 --> 01:46:03,530
Those kids.

1468
01:46:05,530 --> 01:46:09,080
Why do they hate me so much?

1469
01:47:47,510 --> 01:47:50,510
Hi, I'm Dick Nixon.

1470
01:47:50,590 --> 01:47:52,300
Hi, there.

1471
01:47:54,050 --> 01:47:56,020
- Where you from?
- Syracuse.

1472
01:47:56,100 --> 01:47:59,480
Oh, yeah, the, uh, Orangemen.

1473
01:47:59,560 --> 01:48:02,150
Now, there's a football program.

1474
01:48:02,230 --> 01:48:06,440
Jim Brown and that other tailback,

1475
01:48:06,530 --> 01:48:09,650
- the one with the blood disease.
- Ernie Davis.

1476
01:48:09,740 --> 01:48:11,740
Yeah, right, right, right.

1477
01:48:11,990 --> 01:48:15,700
I used to play a little ball myself
at Whittier.

1478
01:48:15,780 --> 01:48:20,870
Of course, they used
to use me as a tackling dummy.

1479
01:48:20,960 --> 01:48:23,420
We didn't come here
to talk about football.

1480
01:48:25,880 --> 01:48:27,670
Yeah, I understand that.

1481
01:48:29,010 --> 01:48:32,640
- How old are you, young lady?
- Nineteen.

1482
01:48:33,340 --> 01:48:34,640
Yeah.

1483
01:48:35,550 --> 01:48:40,230
Well, probably most of you think
I'm a real SOB. I know that.

1484
01:48:40,310 --> 01:48:42,900
I understand how you feel.
But, you know,

1485
01:48:42,980 --> 01:48:45,690
I want peace too.
But peace with honor.

1486
01:48:45,770 --> 01:48:48,070
- What does that mean?
- Bullshit.

1487
01:48:48,150 --> 01:48:51,740
Well, you can't have peace
without a price.

1488
01:48:51,820 --> 01:48:55,490
Sometimes you have to be
willing to fight for peace,

1489
01:48:55,570 --> 01:48:57,580
and sometimes to die.

1490
01:48:57,660 --> 01:49:01,410
Yeah? Tell that to the GIs who are
gonna die tomorrow in Vietnam.

1491
01:49:01,500 --> 01:49:05,080
- What lets you kill women and children?
- What you have to understand

1492
01:49:05,170 --> 01:49:08,090
is we're willing to die
for what we believe in.

1493
01:49:08,170 --> 01:49:10,170
- That's the truth.
- Yeah.

1494
01:49:10,260 --> 01:49:11,670
Yeah.

1495
01:49:13,800 --> 01:49:17,600
Look, that man up there,
he lived in similar times.

1496
01:49:17,680 --> 01:49:22,020
Oh, he had chaos, civil war,
hatred between the races.

1497
01:49:22,100 --> 01:49:26,440
- This is all bullshit.
- Sometimes I go to the Lincoln Room

1498
01:49:26,520 --> 01:49:29,980
at the White House and just pray.
But, you know,

1499
01:49:30,070 --> 01:49:34,280
liberals act like idealism
belongs to them.

1500
01:49:34,360 --> 01:49:36,780
That's not true.

1501
01:49:36,870 --> 01:49:42,710
My family went Republican
because Lincoln freed the slaves.

1502
01:49:42,790 --> 01:49:45,000
My grandmother was an abolitionist.

1503
01:49:45,080 --> 01:49:49,210
It was Quakers who founded Whittier,
my hometown...

1504
01:49:49,300 --> 01:49:52,130
- Address the issues.
- ...to abolish slavery.

1505
01:49:52,210 --> 01:49:55,300
They were, you know,
conservative Bible folk,

1506
01:49:55,380 --> 01:49:59,350
but they had a powerful sense
of right and wrong.

1507
01:49:59,430 --> 01:50:02,810
Forty years ago,
I was like you.

1508
01:50:02,890 --> 01:50:07,480
- Looking for answers. See?
- Come on.

1509
01:50:07,560 --> 01:50:09,480
Tricky Dick himself.

1510
01:50:10,570 --> 01:50:15,780
My mother used to feed hobos
stopping over at our house.

1511
01:50:15,860 --> 01:50:17,320
We got him.

1512
01:50:17,410 --> 01:50:19,120
- Don't push, pig.
- Move away.

1513
01:50:19,200 --> 01:50:22,450
It's OK, Bob, we're just rapping,
my friends and I.

1514
01:50:22,540 --> 01:50:25,250
In fact, we agree on a lot of things,
don't we?

1515
01:50:25,330 --> 01:50:28,670
No, we don't.
You say you want to end the war,

1516
01:50:28,750 --> 01:50:34,380
- so why don't you?
- Change always comes slowly.

1517
01:50:35,420 --> 01:50:37,510
I pulled out more than half the troops.

1518
01:50:37,590 --> 01:50:41,140
I'm trying to cut the military budget
for the first time in 30 years.

1519
01:50:41,220 --> 01:50:43,180
I want a volunteer army.

1520
01:50:43,270 --> 01:50:46,140
But it's also a question
of American credibility.

1521
01:50:46,230 --> 01:50:48,980
- Our position in the world.
- Come on, Mr. Nixon.

1522
01:50:49,060 --> 01:50:53,730
- It's a civil war between Vietnamese.
- You don't want the war.

1523
01:50:53,820 --> 01:50:57,360
We don't want the war.
The Vietnamese don't want the war.

1524
01:50:57,450 --> 01:50:59,450
So why does it go on?

1525
01:51:04,950 --> 01:51:07,250
- You should be going, Mr. President.
- OK.

1526
01:51:07,920 --> 01:51:09,250
Please.

1527
01:51:12,290 --> 01:51:14,550
You can't stop it, can you?

1528
01:51:15,510 --> 01:51:17,170
Even if you wanted to.

1529
01:51:17,260 --> 01:51:21,010
'Cause it's not you, it's the system.

1530
01:51:21,100 --> 01:51:24,100
The system won't let you stop it.

1531
01:51:27,600 --> 01:51:30,560
There's... There's more at stake here

1532
01:51:30,650 --> 01:51:33,230
than what you want or what I want.

1533
01:51:33,320 --> 01:51:34,730
Then what's the point?

1534
01:51:34,820 --> 01:51:38,400
What's the point of being president?
You're powerless!

1535
01:51:38,490 --> 01:51:41,820
No! No, I'm not powerless.

1536
01:51:41,910 --> 01:51:44,740
Because I understand the system,
I believe I can...

1537
01:51:44,830 --> 01:51:48,210
I can control it,
maybe not control it totally,

1538
01:51:48,290 --> 01:51:51,040
but tame it enough
to make it do some good.

1539
01:51:52,420 --> 01:51:55,090
Sounds like you're talking
about a wild animal.

1540
01:51:58,420 --> 01:52:00,550
Yeah, maybe I am.

1541
01:52:00,630 --> 01:52:03,220
We really must go,
Mr. President. Please.

1542
01:52:03,300 --> 01:52:07,350
- Hey, what about the war, man?
- When you gonna get us out?

1543
01:52:07,430 --> 01:52:10,440
- The old man's moving.
- Move it. Get away.

1544
01:52:10,520 --> 01:52:13,190
She got it, Bob.
Nineteen-year-old college kid.

1545
01:52:13,270 --> 01:52:15,610
- What? Who?
- She understood something

1546
01:52:15,690 --> 01:52:18,610
that's taken me 25 years
in politics to understand.

1547
01:52:18,690 --> 01:52:22,360
The CIA, the Mafia,
those Wall Street bastards.

1548
01:52:22,450 --> 01:52:24,620
- Sir?
- The beast.

1549
01:52:24,700 --> 01:52:28,120
Nineteen-year-old kid.
She called it a wild animal.

1550
01:52:28,200 --> 01:52:29,710
Yes, sir.

1551
01:52:53,600 --> 01:52:57,480
<i>In Washington, the size
of the crowds have swelled to over</i>

1552
01:52:57,570 --> 01:53:01,650
<i>a quarter of a million demonstrators
protesting the ongoing war in Vietnam.</i>

1553
01:53:01,740 --> 01:53:04,490
There must be
a quarter million out there.

1554
01:53:04,570 --> 01:53:08,410
They've been at it for a whole year.
Young kids just like Tricia.

1555
01:53:10,160 --> 01:53:13,290
You think they got a point, Edgar?

1556
01:53:13,370 --> 01:53:19,090
- This whole damn system of government.
- Remember what Lenin said in 1917.

1557
01:53:19,170 --> 01:53:21,550
The power was lying in the street.

1558
01:53:21,630 --> 01:53:24,300
Just waiting for someone to pick it up.

1559
01:53:24,380 --> 01:53:26,680
Communists have never
been closer than now.

1560
01:53:26,760 --> 01:53:30,020
Now is the time to get back
to the old themes.

1561
01:53:30,100 --> 01:53:32,850
The ones that made you president.

1562
01:53:32,940 --> 01:53:35,350
Let the communists
know you're on to them.

1563
01:53:35,440 --> 01:53:38,650
Little bastards think they can
ruin Tricia's wedding

1564
01:53:38,730 --> 01:53:41,190
by dancing naked in the reflection pool.

1565
01:53:41,280 --> 01:53:44,200
Don't listen to 'em.
And don't quit.

1566
01:53:45,110 --> 01:53:48,450
Remember, Kennedy and King
were against the war.

1567
01:53:48,530 --> 01:53:50,330
Where are they now?

1568
01:53:52,410 --> 01:53:55,920
How the hell The Times got a hold of
this Ellsberg stuff is a disgrace.

1569
01:53:57,750 --> 01:54:00,460
Yeah. We can't keep a damn secret
in this government.

1570
01:54:00,550 --> 01:54:03,380
They're stealing papers
right out of this office.

1571
01:54:03,470 --> 01:54:05,590
Johnson had the same damn problem

1572
01:54:05,680 --> 01:54:08,720
- until he bugged his own office.
- We took that system out.

1573
01:54:08,800 --> 01:54:11,270
That was a mistake.

1574
01:54:11,350 --> 01:54:14,480
The White House was full
of Kennedy people then.

1575
01:54:14,560 --> 01:54:17,520
- It still is.
- Who's behind this?

1576
01:54:17,600 --> 01:54:21,940
Well, you have CIA people
all over this place.

1577
01:54:22,030 --> 01:54:26,410
Helms has seen to that.
Then there's Kissinger's staff.

1578
01:54:26,490 --> 01:54:30,580
Kissinger himself, I believe,
may be the leaker.

1579
01:54:30,660 --> 01:54:32,240
- Kissinger?
- Hmm.

1580
01:54:32,330 --> 01:54:35,080
He's obsessed with his own image.

1581
01:54:35,160 --> 01:54:38,420
He wants his Nobel Peace Prize
a little too much.

1582
01:54:38,500 --> 01:54:41,250
And as the late Dr. King proved,

1583
01:54:41,340 --> 01:54:44,630
even an ape can win a prize
with good press.

1584
01:54:44,720 --> 01:54:47,760
Jesus, I'd like to book him
into a psychiatrist's office.

1585
01:54:47,840 --> 01:54:51,600
He comes in here ranting and raving,
dumping his crap all over the place.

1586
01:54:53,470 --> 01:54:56,940
- Could you prove it, Edgar?
- Mr. President,

1587
01:54:57,020 --> 01:54:59,020
I always get my man.

1588
01:55:00,400 --> 01:55:01,940
Yeah, you do.

1589
01:55:02,020 --> 01:55:05,320
This damn tie. Could you help me?

1590
01:55:05,400 --> 01:55:06,820
Yeah.

1591
01:55:10,530 --> 01:55:13,700
- See, I'd be bugging myself.
- Look.

1592
01:55:15,370 --> 01:55:19,630
- Who'd get the tapes?
- No one. Your property.

1593
01:55:20,710 --> 01:55:22,790
And it would prove your case.

1594
01:55:22,880 --> 01:55:26,670
Why do you think Kissinger
is taping all your calls?

1595
01:55:27,840 --> 01:55:29,680
For history.

1596
01:55:30,970 --> 01:55:32,800
His word against yours.

1597
01:55:32,890 --> 01:55:36,310
And right now, he's got the records.

1598
01:55:40,560 --> 01:55:43,070
I'll get Manolo to do this.

1599
01:55:43,650 --> 01:55:45,780
Thanks.

1600
01:55:45,860 --> 01:55:47,990
You know, Churchill once said to me,

1601
01:55:48,070 --> 01:55:50,490
"If you want your own
history written properly,

1602
01:55:50,570 --> 01:55:52,570
you better write it yourself."

1603
01:55:52,660 --> 01:55:54,790
The only thing is, Edgar,

1604
01:55:54,870 --> 01:55:57,250
I don't want this to come back
and haunt me.

1605
01:55:57,330 --> 01:56:00,210
It won't, as long as I'm here.

1606
01:56:00,870 --> 01:56:02,380
Good.

1607
01:56:09,090 --> 01:56:10,680
This way.

1608
01:56:16,100 --> 01:56:17,810
What's wrong?

1609
01:56:18,810 --> 01:56:21,270
We're just not going
to buckle to these people.

1610
01:56:21,350 --> 01:56:23,440
No more war!

1611
01:56:30,280 --> 01:56:32,450
- It's beautiful.
- OK.

1612
01:56:37,290 --> 01:56:38,540
Yes, thank you.

1613
01:56:48,130 --> 01:56:50,970
Princess, may I?

1614
01:56:52,300 --> 01:56:53,800
Thank you.

1615
01:57:06,820 --> 01:57:10,400
I'm very proud of you today,
Princess. Very.

1616
01:57:10,490 --> 01:57:11,820
